player.seasonOutlook: There were times last season where Kyrou seemed to be extremely quiet for long stretches at a time, but he still somehow finished with 37 goals, shattering his previous high-water mark of 27 set just a year prior. The increased goal total was the direct result of Kyrou getting more pucks on net. His shot total rose from 188 in 2021-22 to 272 in 2022-23. He also added 23 points with the man advantage. That's the good news. The bad news was Kyrou's minus-38 rating, a number that torpedoed his fantasy value in leagues which value that statistic. Kyrou offers very little in terms of hits and blocks, so he's going to have to continue to put up points to be worthy of an early-round fantasy selection in 2023-24.

Barzal's 2022-23 season was  derailed by a lower-body issue which cost him nearly two months from mid-February to mid-April. He returned for the Islanders' six-game, first-round loss to Carolina in the playoffs, managing two goals and zero assists in that series. Barzal won the Calder Trophy as NHL Rookie of the Year back in 2017-18 after posting 22 goals and 85 points in 82 games. He's finished with no more than 19 goals and 62 points in the five years since. Now 26 years old, Barzal is locked into a top-line role for the Islanders, but they project as one of the NHL's lowest-scoring teams and had one of the worst power plays in the league last year. Barzal is a reasonable mid-to-late round pick in fantasy drafts, but don't overpay for production that is unlikely to materialize.

Those that rolled the dice on Pettersson in fantasy drafts in 2022-23 in hopes of a breakout campaign got their wish. The Swede set new career-best marks in goals (39), assists (63), points (102), shots on goal (257) and average ice time (20:33). He also finished with 25 power-play points, the second straight year in which he's reached that plateau. There's a real chance the Canucks miss the postseason again in 2023-24 considering they'll be rolling out virtually the same roster that finished a dozen points out of a playoff spot a year ago, but Pettersson is going to put up gaudy numbers regardless.

Dobson looked like a prime breakout candidate in his age-23 season in 2022-23, his fourth in the NHL, but it never really materialized. In fact, his final numbers (13 goals, 49 points, 206 shots on goal, 19 power-play points) were eerily similar to his statistics from the year prior (13 goals, 51 points, 190 shots on goal, 22 power-play points). Part of that was due to the fact the Islanders were truly awful with the man advantage, converting at a 15.8 percent clip, 30th in the league ahead of only Anaheim and Philadelphia. The optimistic point of view is Dobson was still able to put up solid offensive numbers despite his team's power-play struggles, so perhaps he could take another step forward if that unit improves in 2023-24. Either way, consider him a solid mid-round fantasy target on draft day.

In a year in which virtually nothing went right in St. Louis, Buchnevich was one of the few bright spots. He averaged more than a point-per-game (26 goals, 67 points in 63 games) for a second straight season, although he also dealt with multiple ailments throughout the year. His 21 points with the man advantage were a career high. That said, Buchnevich is a prime regression candidate from a goals-scored standpoint following a year in which he converted his shots at an outlandish 21.1 percent, far higher than anything we have seen in the past. The 26 goals he scored came on just 123 shots on goal. Buchnevich is quite likely to produce mid-round fantasy value when healthy, but the injury concern here is real, so take that into consideration on draft day.

Father Time gets everyone eventually, but he hasn't found Crosby yet and there are zero signs he's even close. "Sid The Kid" played in all 82 games for Pittsburgh a season ago, averaging more than a point-per-game (93 points) for an 18th straight year, or, in other words, every season he's been in the league. Crosby's 33 goals in 2022-23 were his most since the 2018-19 campaign. He also posted 25-plus power-play points (27) for the fifth time in seven years. Crosby is a slightly greater injury risk than some of the other top players in the game, but he's also a lock for elite-level offensive production whenever he's in the lineup.

Reinhart got off to a dreadful start last season, managing just five points in Florida's first 15 games. He was better the rest of the way, but his overall numbers (31 goals, 67 points in 82 games) were down compared to his better than a point-per-game pace (33 goals, 82 points in 78 games) in his first season with the Panthers. Reinhart's power-play production remained elite, as he posted 27 points with the man advantage while averaging a ridiculous 4:00 of power-play time per game. Reinhart also set a new career high with 227 shots on goal, although his 13.7 shooting percentage was his lowest mark since 2018-19. There's a high floor here from a fantasy perspective with the potential for more if Reinhart gets a bit more luck in 2023-24.

With Johnny Gaudreau signing with Columbus and Matthew Tkachuk traded to Florida, Lindholm lost both of his running mates from his breakout 2021-22 campaign (42G, 82P in 82GP) last year, and his production suffered as a result. Lindholm's overall offensive numbers (22G, 64P in 80GP) were way down despite the fact his production with the man advantage (21P) improved a tad. The biggest decline of all came in the plus-minus department, where Lindholm went from a ridiculous plus-61 in 2021-22 to just a plus-six rating a year ago. Lindholm is a potential bounce-back candidate this year and he'll likely be available at a decent discount in drafts, but keep in mind he's also a pending free agent who could be traded at the deadline assuming he doesn't want to re-sign with Calgary.

Letang appeared in 64 games for the Penguins in 2022-23, a remarkable total considering he dealt with a lower-body injury in addition to suffering the second stroke of his career. Letang played in all of Pittsburgh's final 31 contests, so he should be full healthy for training camp. He's continued to produce like a top-flight fantasy defender when in the lineup, but Pittsburgh's acquisition of Erik Karlsson will likely result in Letang being demoted to the No. 2 power-play unit this year, hampering his fantasy value and scoring upside significantly.

Loving life in his first season playing alongside the likes of Connor McDavid and Leon Draisaitl, Hyman set new high-water marks across the board a year ago, finishing with 36 goals, 47 assists, 83 points, 276 shots on goal and 26 power-play points while averaging a career-best 20:09 worth of playing time per game. Hyman is certainly talented enough to deposit whatever scoring chances are set up for him by his teammates, but more so than any other Oiler, Hyman seems to be at the greatest risk for decreased production if either McDavid or Draisaitl sustains an injury. As is, Hyman should be considered a mid-round fantasy pick with nice upside in 2023-24.

Weegar was effective enough from a fantasy standpoint in 2022-23, but he took a significant step back from his breakout 2021-22 campaign, his final with the Panthers. Weegar managed 31 points, 160 shots on goal, 186 hits, 117 blocks and a plus-15 rating in 81 games for the Flames last year. He's tallied exactly three power-play points in three straight seasons, so he shouldn't be considered an asset with the man advantage. Weegar's average ice time also dipped from 23:22 two years ago to 21:06 last season. Those that participate in formats that don't value hits, blocks and plus-minus rating may want to look elsewhere on draft day this year.

Larsson was a legitimate multi-category fantasy weapon in 2022-23. Playing in all 82 games for the Kraken for a second straight campaign, Larsson scored eight goals and set a new career high with 33 points. He also posted a plus-27 rating in addition to crushing it in terms of both hits (222) and blocks (173), per usual. Larsson's offensive game may not have developed as many hoped after the Devils took him No. 4 overall in 2011, but he's a no-doubt, top-four defender on a good team. There's mid-round value here if your format values both hits and blocks. Invest with confidence.

Thompson came out of nowhere to post 38 goals and 68 points in 78 games in 2021-22. Those who thought the breakout was a fluke and avoided the big man in fantasy drafts last fall paid for it, as he improved on those gaudy numbers, finishing with 47 goals and 94 points in 78 games. Thompson's 20 goals with the man advantage last year tied him with Tampa Bay's Brayden Point and Mika Zibanejad of the Rangers for third most in the NHL. It took time, but it's abundantly clear at this point that Thompson is a top-flight NHL player. It's dangerous to forecast any improvement considering how well Thompson played in 2022-23, but the Sabres are a team on the rise and a slight uptick in production can't be completely ruled out.

The No. 1 overall selection in 2018, Dahlin finally put together the breakout season many had been expecting for a while in 2022-23. His 73 points in 78 games tied him with Dallas' Miro Heiskanen and Florida's Brandon Montour for third among all NHL rearguards in scoring. Dahlin's 204 shots on goal were a new personal high-water mark, while his plus-12 rating was also a welcome sight considering he finished the 2020-21 and 2021-22 seasons with a combined minus-58 rating. Toss in the fact Dahlin posted more than 200 hits and blocks (237) for a second straight year and you have a well-rounded fantasy asset that projects as a rock-solid No. 1 defensive option heading into the 2023-24 campaign.

Anyone that spent a pick on Parayko in fantasy drafts last year hoping for a bounce-back effort likely came away a bit disappointed. He managed just 27 points in 79 games, the lowest total of his career in any season in which he's appeared in at least 64 contests. Once a capable power-play performer, Parayko has just three assists with the man advantage in his last 191 games. He did add 259 combined hits/blocks last year, so he'll continue to have value in fantasy leagues that place an emphasis on those stats, just don't expect much more than five goals and 30 points from the 30-year-old blueliner in 2023-24.

Virtually all of Matthews' numbers in 2022-23 were right in line with his 60-goal, 106-point breakout campaign of 2021-22, but his shooting percentage dipped to a career-low 12.2 and his production (40 goals, 85 points) suffered as a result. The good news is Matthews has now scored 40-plus goals in four straight years while averaging better than a point-per-game in six straight seasons. He could easily threaten the 50-goal plateau in 2023-24 with just a minor rebound to his shooting percentage, which, combined with his elite power-play production (28 points in 2022-23), make the No. 1 overall pick from 2016 a no-doubt first-rounder in all fantasy formats.

Like most of his Vancouver teammates, Boeser's 2022-23 campaign was a bit of a mixed bag. He scored just 18 goals in 74 games, but his 37 assists were a new career high and Boeser's 55 points were his most since the 2018-19 season. He also finished with a career-worst minus-20 rating. Boeser has long been a steady, if unspectacular, power-play performer, posting somewhere between 14-17 points with the man advantage in each of the past five years. How much value Boeser possesses is dependent on your format, but fantasy managers seeking players with high ceilings should look elsewhere.

Eichel missed the better part of a month early in the 2022-23 season with a lower-body injury, but his surgically repaired neck was never an issue in a year which culminated in the Golden Knights winning the Stanley Cup for the first time. Eichel just missed out on averaging a point-per-game for the third time in his career (27 goals, 66 points in 67 games), but he exploded in the postseason, leading all players in both assists (20) and points (26 in 22 games). The lone concern was the fact Eichel managed just 14 points with the man advantage. His 2:39 worth of power-play time per game was the lowest mark of his career. Still, Eichel does so many other things well that at age 26, the Massachusetts native is well worth an early-round fantasy pick on draft day.

Ekholm was a godsend for the Oilers in 2022-23 following a late February trade from Nashville, logging key minutes in all situations and providing Edmonton with a much-needed steadying presence on the blue line. Ekholm posted four goals and 14 points in 21 games with his new club after managing just five goals and 18 points in 57 games with the Predators. Ekholm was a big scorer as recently as a few years ago, having tallied 44 points in the 2018-19 campaign. He's not that type of player anymore, but he should once again be good for 30-plus points, 150-plus hits/blocks and a solid plus-minus rating in 2023-24, giving the Swede legitimate value in deeper fantasy formats.

Buoyed by an outlandish 16.4 shooting percentage, the second highest number of his 15-year career, Giroux set a new career-best mark in goals in his first season with the Senators with 35 in 2022-23. Giroux's 79 points were his most since the 2018-19 season, and he also added 20-plus points with the man advantage (24) for the eleventh time in the past twelve years. Giroux will be 36 years of age in January, so there's likely some regression on the horizon, particularly in the goals-scored category, but there's still enough all-around production here to make the Hearst, Ontario native worthy of a pick on draft day.

The best and most dynamic player in a league full of superstars, McDavid is coming off a season in which he led the league in goals (64), assists (89), points (153) and power play points (71) on his way to winning his third Hart Trophy as the NHL's Most Valuable Player. McDavid added new career-best marks in shots on goal (352) and hits (89) for good measure. Simply put, there is no player in the league that can match the consistent and elite production of a healthy McDavid over the course of a full season. Still just 26 years of age, the Edmonton captain is the no-doubt, unquestioned No. 1 overall fantasy pick in every format this year.

Two seasons into an eight-year, $74 million deal he signed in August of 2021, Nurse is coming off his best fantasy season to date. He played in all 82 games for the Oilers a year ago, finishing with 12 goals and a career-high 43 points while adding 203 shots on goal, 146 hits, 194 blocks and a plus-26 rating. The only negative thing you can point to regarding Nurse from a fantasy standpoint is he doesn't contribute much of anything with the man advantage anymore, managing just a lone power-play assist last season. Nurse's value is heavily tilted toward formats which value hits and blocks, in which he is one of the most valuable defenders in the league. In other formats, he's more of a mid-to-late round player.

Miller's 2022-23 performance would have to be termed as a bit of a disappointment. He scored 32 goals for a second straight season and averaged more than a point-per-game (82 points in 81 games) once again, but that's where the good comes to an end. Miller's name came up in trade rumors despite the fact the Canucks had just signed him to an eight-year, $56 million deal right before training camp. His assist total dropped from 67 to 50, and he finished with eight fewer points with the man advantage (30) despite averaging 40 seconds more of power-play time per game. However, Vancouver was a terrible team last season, and Miller still produced pretty admirably, so perhaps things aren't as bleak as they appeared last year.

Banged up for a good portion of the 2021-22 campaign, Point played in all 82 games for the Lightning in 2022-23 and responded with career-best marks in both goals (51) and points (95). He was one of just five players to reach the 50-goal mark along with Connor McDavid, David Pastrnak, Mikko Rantanen and Leon Draisaitl. Point also added 30 points with the man advantage, marking the first time since 2018-19 in which he reached that plateau. Point is due for some regression due to his 21.7 shooting percentage from last season, but he's locked into a first line and top power-play unit role on a high-powered offense, making him an obvious early-round target in fantasy drafts this year.

Ehlers played just two games for the Jets at the start of the 2022-23 season before undergoing sports hernia surgery and missing two and a half months of action. He played in every game for Winnipeg the rest of the way before suffering an upper-body injury which cost him the team's regular-season finale and four of the five games in its first-round playoff series loss to Vegas. Ehlers finished the year with a dozen goals and 38 points in 45 games. He should be ready to roll for training camp, making Ehlers a clear bounce-back candidate from a fantasy perspective in 2023-24. His 9.1 shooting percentage last season was his lowest mark since his 2015-16 rookie campaign, meaning he is due for some positive regression in addition to a return to presumed full health.

There's nothing flashy about Pettersson's game, but he's been a reliable stay-at-home defender for the Penguins for years now. He missed 12 of Pittsburgh's final 13 games with a lower-body injury, but the issue is not a long-term concern. The Swede has finished with somewhere between 19-25 points in four of the past five seasons, and his 264 combined hits/blocks in 2022-23 were a new career high. In fantasy formats that reward hits and blocks, Pettersson will be worthy of a later-round pick on draft day.

One of the most consistent defenders in the game from both a fantasy and real-life perspective, Pietrangelo was his usual excellent self for the Golden Knights in 2022-23. He finished with 54 points in 73 games, his highest total since the 2017-18 campaign with St. Louis. Pietrangelo added 170 shots on goal, 14 power-play points, 65 hits and a career-best 177 blocks. He appeared in 21 of 22 games in Vegas' run to the Stanley Cup, with the only contest he sat out being the result of a one-game suspension following a slash to Edmonton's Leon Draisaitl. Pietrangelo has displayed no signs of slowing down despite the fact he'll turn 34 next January, making him a rock-solid fantasy option in all formats this year.

The Canucks have made plenty of strange moves over the past few years but trading a first and a second-round pick to Detroit in exchange for Hronek a few days before the deadline last March might take the cake. He had a shoulder injury at the time of the deal, eventually returning for four games late in the month before Vancouver shut him down. All told, Hronek posted a career-high 39 points (16 with the man advantage) in 64 games between the Canucks and Red Wings. Quinn Hughes is Vancouver's unquestioned power-play quarterback, but the team may plan to play two defenders on its top unit, otherwise the trade for Hronek makes little sense. Monitor the situation in training camp.

Svechnikov played in all of Carolina's first 64 games of the 2022-23 season before suffering a serious knee injury which required surgery and ended his year. His production prior to the ailment-- 32 goals, 55 points, 205 shots on goal, 16 power-play points, 140 hits-- was right in line with what we saw from him over a 78-game clip in 2021-22. Svechnikov reportedly began skating in July, meaning he should be fine for the start of the upcoming season assuming he suffers no setbacks along the way. Drafting a player coming off such a significant injury is a little scary, but Svechnikov has league-winning potential if everything comes together for the young sniper.

The early returns for the Flames on the deal that brought Huberdeau and Mackenzie Weegar in from Florida in exchange for Matthew Tkachuk last year haven't been great. Huberdeau looked like an obvious regression candidate after finishing second in the NHL in scoring (115 points in 80 games) two seasons ago, but nobody could have foreseen a Calgary debut in which he managed just 15 goals and 55 points in 79 games. As is typically the case, the truth likely lies somewhere in the middle. Huberdeau has eight years left on a contract that pays him $10.5 annually, so both he and the Flames are going to have to figure out a way to right the ship. That may be difficult for a Calgary team whose offensive depth appears to be dwindling by the day, but there's no escape hatch here for either side.

Doughty was bit hard by the injury bug in 2021-22, as he was limited to just 39 games, but he played in 81 of 82 contests for the Kings last season, finishing with nine goals and 52 points, his highest totals since the 2017-18 campaign. Doughty's 27 points with the man advantage last year were the most in any one season of his storied career, and he also posted 200-plus hits/blocks (219) for the thirteenth time in fifteen years. LA traded Sean Durzi to Arizona this offseason, eliminating one of Doughty's potential threats to steal power-play time. It's risky betting on a soon-to-be 34-year-old defender with nearly 1,100 games of NHL experience under his belt, but Doughty should remain a solid all-around fantasy option for at least one more year.

Thomas' production with the man advantage improved considerably last season, as he posted a career-best 22 power-play points compared to just 14 during the 2021-22 season, but not much else went right. He finished with 65 points in 73 games, a far cry from the 77 points in 72 games we saw from him in 2021-22. Thomas is difficult to get a read on from a fantasy perspective. He's a gifted playmaker, but it's very hard to provide consistent value when you never shoot the puck. Over the past two seasons combined, Thomas has just 221 shots on goal in 145 games, a stunningly low number for a guy that otherwise projects as a solid mid-round fantasy asset. He deserves a boost in formats that place an additional emphasis on assists, just don't expect much more than 20 goals from him in 2023-24.

Andersson was Calgary's best defensemen last season, posting a career-high 11 goals while also finishing with 49 points, including 21 with the man advantage. The Swede is due for some regression following a campaign in which he posted a 6.9 shooting percentage, by far his highest number to date, but Andersson remains a lock for mid-round fantasy production given the fact he averaged north of 24 minutes of ice time per game (24:05) last season, a figure that should remain steady in 2023-24. Keep Andersson's name in mind once you get past the top tier of defenders in your draft this fall.

Running as hot as the sun, Horvat began the 2022-23 campaign in Vancouver, posting 31 goals and 54 points in 49 games. He was traded to the Islanders in late January, a move that led to his production dipping significantly. He finished with seven goals and 16 points in 30 games with his new club, numbers right in line with what we've seen from him in prior years. The Islanders handed Horvat a new eight-year, $68 million dollar deal shortly after the trade was completed, which pays Horvat like a No. 1 center. That's a stretch, but the Islanders lack offensive weapons and Horvat certainly fills that need. His previous high-water mark in terms of scoring heading into last season was 31 goals and 52 points in 70 games back in 2021-22, but it wouldn't be surprising to see him surpass those totals while skating in a featured role for the Isles in 2023-24.

While Barkov by no means played poorly in 2022-23 (23 goals, 78 points in 68 games), he was a minor disappointment from a fantasy perspective. The root of that was the fact Barkov has dealt with nagging injuries in recent years. He's played no more than those previously mentioned 68 games in a season dating back to the 2018-19 campaign. The optimistic point of view would be that Barkov posted 30 points with the man advantage (30) for the second time in his career last year and still put-up reasonable scoring numbers despite an 11.1 percent shooting percentage, his worst mark in half a decade. The injury risk here is real and considerably higher than many other players that will go early in your fantasy draft, but the upside is significant.

Seemingly on the trade block for years, Chychrun was finally traded from Arizona to Ottawa in early March. He missed the first five weeks of the season with a wrist injury, was benched another three weeks just prior to the trade for "asset protection" and then suffered a hamstring injury which cost him the Senators' final ten regular-season games. All told, Chychrun appeared in just 48 contests, posting nine goals and 33 points. This came on the heels of a 2021-22 campaign in which he played in just 47 games. Chychrun is an easy mid-round fantasy option from a pure talent perspective, but he's constantly banged up and there's no guarantee he'll be on Ottawa's top power-play unit this year with Thomas Chabot also in the mix. The upside here is significant, but the floor is downright scary.

Those hoping for a breakout season from Cozens last year got all they could have asked for and then some. The 22-year-old finished with 31 goals and 68 points (18 with the man advantage) in 81 games just a year removed from a campaign in which he managed just 13 goals and 38 points in 79 games. The Sabres are clear believers, as Buffalo handed Cozens a shiny new seven-year, $49.7 million deal in February. The No. 7 overall selection from 2019 won't turn 23 until next February, making him a highly sought after mid-round re-draft option and an elite keeper/dynasty league asset.

Skjei scored 18 goals in 2022-23, doubling his previous high-water mark he set in 2021-22. He flirted with the 40-point mark (38) once again, and his seven power-play points were his most since his 2016-17 rookie season with the Rangers. Unfortunately, a repeat performance seems unlikely. Skjei's 9.6 shooting percentage was way higher than usual for him, and the addition of Tony DeAngelo to the Carolina lineup via free agency means Skjei;s power-play time is likely to dry up in 2023-24. Don't overpay for past production on draft day.

Those banking on a breakout year from Caufield in 2022-23 got their wish... sort of. The diminutive sniper posted a whopping 26 goals in 46 games before undergoing shoulder surgery which ended his year. Caufield separated his shoulder twice, once in late December and again in mid-January before he and the Canadiens decided to get the issue repaired during a season in which the team was going nowhere. Clearly comfortable with Caufield's long-term prognosis, Montreal handed him an eight-year, $62.8 million deal in early June. The University of Wisconsin product should be fully healthy for training camp and could easily threaten the 40-goal mark in 2023-24, health permitting.

Matheson set a new career high in points last season, picking up 34 in just 48 games. He finished the year on fire, notching 10 points in his final 11 contests. Matheson's breakout was directly tied to a massive bump in usage. He averaged a ridiculous 24:27 of ice time per game, including 3:11 with the man advantage. Any rearguard that plays that much is worth a look from a fantasy standpoint. Matheson should be considered the favorite to quarterback the Canadiens' No. 1 power-play unit in 2023-24, making him an interesting later-round option in this year's drafts.

Debuting in Florida in 2022-23 after six seasons with Calgary, Tkachuk finished third in voting for the Hart Trophy as the NHL's Most Valuable Player thanks to a campaign in which he posted 40 goals and a career-high 109 points in 79 games. Tkachuk added new high-water marks in both shots on goal (322) and power-play points (36), as well. Aleksander Barkov is the Panthers' captain, but Tkachuk is unquestionably the team's most important and indispensable player. We now have back-to-back seasons of elite production from Tkachuk with two different clubs. That makes him worthy of a first-round pick in all fantasy formats.

Guentzel was his usual steady self from a fantasy perspective in 2022-23, posting 35-plus goals (36) and 70-plus points (73) for the third time in five years. Guentzel also set a new career high with 23 points with the man advantage, while his 243 shots on goal were his second-highest mark to date. Guentzel is obviously an excellent player in his own right, but his fantasy value is significantly boosted by the fact he lines up alongside Sidney Crosby every night. Sid appeared in all 82 games for the Penguins a year ago and will play this entire season at age 36, so Guentzel's numbers could take a minor hit if Crosby is out with an injury for an extended period in 2023-24.

Danault's goal total was way down (18 in 82 games) last season compared to 2021-22 (27 in 79 games), but his assist numbers were way up, and the result was a new career-best 54 points. Danault averaged nearly the exact same amount of power-play time per game (2:04) in 2022-23 as the previous year (2:03), but his production with the man advantage increased from a measly four points two campaigns ago to 20 last season. The acquisition of Pierre-Luc Dubois from the Jets this summer means Danault will likely serve as LA's No. 3 center in 2023-24, which will lengthen the Kings' lineup considerably, even if it means Danault will probably see his offensive output dip a bit.

No Carolina player was as disappointing in 2022-23 from a fantasy perspective as Teravainen. An upper-body injury in mid-November cost him three weeks, and an illness also cost him four games late in the year. He then broke his hand in Game 2 of the Hurricanes' first-round playoff series against the Islanders, only to return for Carolina's four-game sweep of the Panthers in the Eastern Conference Final. All told, Teravainen managed just a dozen goals and 37 points in 68 regular-season games. He doesn't shoot much-- he's posted 200-plus shots in just one of his nine NHL seasons-- so it's imperative that he picks up plenty of assists, particularly with the man advantage. He should bounce back to some extent in 2023-24, but we may not see Teravainen threaten the point-per-game pace again anytime soon.

Kucherov was a massive injury risk a season ago on the heels of a 2021-22 campaign in which he played just 47 games, but he ended up not missing a game for the Lightning in either the regular season or the postseason. The Russian wizard finished tied for third in the league in scoring with 113 points, and his 50 points with the man advantage were fourth best in the league and the highest mark for any player that doesn't play for the Oilers. The last three times in which he has appeared in at least 80 games in a season, Kucherov has never failed to reach 100 points. A lock for elite production and with the injury woes seemingly behind him, Kucherov is well worth an early-round pick on draft day.

The offensive explosion of Morrissey was by far one of the most unexpected outcomes of the entire 2022-23 season. A player who had never posted more than a dozen goals and 37 points (15 with the man advantage) in any prior year, he upped those totals to 16 goals and 76 points (including 28 a man up) last season. Morrissey finished tied with Vancouver's Quinn Hughes for second among defensemen in scoring, trailing only San Jose's Erik Karlsson. The question now is how much of that is sustainable? Well, Morrissey's 2022-23 9.3 shooting percentage was a new career high by a wide margin. That said, he averaged 3:42 of power-play time per game after seeing just 2:33 the year prior. To summarize, the truth is probably somewhere in the middle. At least 12 goals and 50-plus points seems like a fair floor for Morrsissey in 2023-24.

Nugent-Hopkins was a legitimate league-winner in fantasy pools in 2022-23, playing in all 82 games for the Oilers and finishing ninth in the NHL in scoring with 104 points. His 67 assists were third most in the league, and his 53 points with the man advantage trailed only teammates Connor McDavid and Leon Draisaitl. That said, there are concerns regarding whether that breakout is sustainable. For starters, Nugent-Hopking 18.4 shooting percentage was way higher than we've seen from him in the past. He's probably a lock for elite power-play production, but a McDavid or Draisaitl injury would be a crippling blow to Edmonton's No. 1 unit. Something closer to 30 goals and 80 points seems like a reasonable expectation for RNH in 2023-24.

Those hoping for Hanifin to take another step forward in 2022-23 didn't get their wish. While he by no means played poorly, Hanifin's numbers (seven goals, 38 points, 176 shots on goal, eight power-play points, plus-2 rating) were all down significantly when compared to the previous year. The big concern at this point is Hanifin's contract situation. He'll be an unrestricted free agent next July and to this point has shown no interest in signing an extension with Calgary. It seems likely that Hanifin will be traded at some point, but when and where remains an open question.

Burns arrived in Carolina last season after 11 years in San Jose and proceeded to post his best scoring total (61 points in 82 games) since the 2018-19 campaign. The production came despite the fact Burns averaged just 23:13 worth of ice time per game, his lowest mark in nearly a decade. It's nerve-racking to bet on any player, especially a point-producing defenseman that will be 39 years of age before the 2023-24 season concludes, but Burns has a skill set that would appear to age better than most. He's a lock to continue to see a ton of time with the man advantage and he's always among the league leaders for shots on goal by a defender, so the future Hall of Famer should make for a safe fantasy selection for at least one more year.

Bennett again proved to be a serviceable middle-six forward option for the Panthers in 2022-23, but he missed 19 of Florida's 82 regular-season games and was banged up throughout the playoffs, although he didn't miss any time in the postseason. Bennett closed with 16 goals, 40 points (9 with the man advantage), 193 shots on goal and 150 hits. His fantasy value is directly tied to how deep your league is. Bennett doesn't project to offer enough all-around production to be worthy of a draft pick in standard 12-team formats, but he's worthy of a roster spot in deeper leagues, especially those that reward hits.

Vilardi is one of the greater injuries risks in the NHL. To give you an idea about his past struggles, he was "fairly healthy" in 2022-23 and still missed 19 games. When active, Vilardi was excellent, posting new career-best marks in goals (23), assists (18), points (41), shots on goal (122) and power-play points (nine). Vilardi was shipped to Winnipeg in the deal that brought Pierre-Luc Dubois to the Kings this summer. Signed to a new two-year, $6.875 million contract, Vilardi will fill the No. 2 center role for the Jets in 2023-24 behind trade candidate Mark Scheifele. Vilardi will be a solid fantasy weapon as long as he remains healthy.

San Jose's decision to hand Hertl a new eight-year, $65.1 contract prior to the 2021-22 trade deadline was an odd move for a team clearly in a rebuild. The Sharks got fair, if unspectacular, value for their investment a season ago, as Hertl managed 22 goals and 63 points (including 22 with the man advantage) in 79 games. He also posted a ghastly minus-36 rating, and San Jose finished with the fourth worst record in the NHL, just two points from the basement. Things don't project to be much better for the Sharks in 2023-24, so while Hertl should still post solid numbers, his upside will be capped to an extent.

Mercer's 2022-23 sophomore season was a resounding success on all fronts. He played in all 82 games for New Jersey for a second straight year, setting new high-water marks in goals (27), assists (29), points (54), shots on goal (161), plus-minus rating (plus-22) and power-play points (10). Mercer had a stretch from mid-February to early March in which he scored at least one goal in eight straight games, posting 15 points during that span. Jack Hughes and Timo Meier seem to get all the publicity up front for New Jersey, and the acquisition of Tyler Toffoli from Calgary won't help matters, but the bottom line is Mercer plays for one of the best young teams in the NHL and won't turn 22 until late October. He should be considered a sneaky mid-round upside pick in all fantasy formats.

Walman had cups of coffee over the course of three seasons with the Blues, but it was a trade to Detroit in March of 2022 which changed the course for the former Providence College product. He joined the Red Wings lineup in mid-November last year, and he was a regular for the team the rest of the way, finishing with nine goals and 18 points in 63 games. After signing a new three-year, $10.2 million contract with Detroit in February, Walman will be locked into a regular role in 2023-24, giving him solid potential as a depth defenseman for fantasy managers in 2023-24.

Now two years into his run with the Islanders, Romanov has settled into a low-upside, stay-at-home defender role that can help fantasy managers in the hits and blocks departments and not much else. His 22 points in 2022-23 were a new career high, but that number gives you an idea of the type of offensive upside Romanov offers on a yearly basis. He has, however, posted 425 hits and 273 blocks over 155 games the Isles, both respectable totals which make Romanov worthy of a later-round pick in drafts depending on the format. He dealt with an upper-body injury late in the year and into the playoffs that required offseason surgery, but Romanov is expected to be ready for training camp.

Kopitar played the entirety of last season at age 35 and finished with 28 goals and 74 points in 82 games, his highest scoring totals since the 2017-18 campaign. Kopitar's 20 points with the man advantage marked the fifth time in the past six years he's reached that mark, while his plus-20 rating was his best mark in half a decade. Kopitar had one year left on his contract, but the Kings, clearly comfortable with where he's at in his career, handed the veteran a two-year, $14 million extension in July. Betting on a 36-year-old is risky, but Kopitar keeps himself in excellent shape and has been extremely durable for most of his career. He should once again be a useful source of secondary scoring for fantasy managers this year.

Draisaitl is coming off his best all-around season to date, which is saying something. He cracked the 50-goal plateau (52) for a second straight year in 2022-23 while also adding new career-best marks in assists (76), points (128) and power-play points (62). He finished second in the league to fellow running mate Connor McDavid in those last two categories. It's difficult to believe the two best fantasy stars in the game can play for the same team, but that's currently the case. A healthy Draisaitl is going to be among the league leaders in all major offensive categories, making him the obvious No. 2 fantasy pick in most formats for 2023-24.

Marner functions as the driving force behind the success of the Maple Leafs. His exceptional vision and hockey IQ position him as one of the premier playmakers in the NHL. Moreover, his competitive spirit and defensive ability further solidify his prowess. Over the last two seasons, Marner has come close to achieving 100 points. In 2023-24, he's poised to reach that milestone while leading the Leafs in scoring. He should also continue to excel with the first power-play unit. Marner is a top-10 talent whose draft position might slip to the end of the first round or even the second round due to the perception that he has a somewhat limited goal-scoring ceiling. Invest with confidence.

Proving his breakout performance from two years ago was no fluke, Bratt played in all 82 games for the Devils a season ago, finishing with 73 points for a second straight year while also potting a career-best 32 goals. The Swede added new high-water marks in shots on goal (212), power-play points (22) and plus-minus rating (plus-14) for good measure. New Jersey will have a full season of Timo Meier in 2023-24 and the team acquired Tyler Toffoli from Calgary, but Bratt is locked into a top-line role on the heels of signing a new eight-year, $63 million deal in mid-June. Health permitting, Bratt should once again be good for roughly 30 goals and 75 points in 2023-24.

Tarasenko's decade-long run with the Blues ended in mid-February following a trade to the Rangers. He played reasonably well in both places, although his 18 goals and 50 points in 69 games is a far cry from the type of production we saw from Tarasenko in his heyday. He reportedly wanted to return to New York this offseason, but the Rangers didn't have the necessary salary cap space. Tarasenko eventually inked a one-year, $5 million deal with Ottawa in late July. It's a so-so landing spot from a fantasy perspective, as Tarasenko isn't a lock to play on the Senators' No. 1 power-play unit, something that would be essential for him to find increased production. The former 40-goal scorer is more of a floor than a ceiling play from a fantasy standpoint at this stage of his career.

There's a real case to be made that Fox deserved to win his second Norris Trophy as the NHL's top defenseman in 2022-23, but Erik Karlsson's 101 points ended up swaying most of the voters. Fox finished second in voting, however, in what was another brilliant season for the 25-year-old. Fox played in all 82 games for the Rangers, posting a career-high 12 goals while cracking the 70-point plateau (72) for a second straight year. He added 159 shots on goal, 29 power-play points and a plus-28 rating, all while averaging 24:23 worth of ice time per game. Fox is as safe of an option as you will find in terms of a No. 1 fantasy defender heading into 2023-24.

Kreider had no chance of matching his ridiculous 52-goal effort from 2021-22 last year, but he still finished with 36 tallies, his second-highest mark to date. That's the good news. The bad news is he managed just 18 assists in 79 games, and his power-play production also dropped considerably. Kreider scored just eight goals with the man advantage a year after leading the entire league with 26. He finished strong, scoring six times in seven games in New York's first-round playoff series loss to the Devils. Kreider is locked in as the Rangers' No. 1 left wing on the team's top line alongside star center Mika Zibanejad, and he'll also continue to serve as the net-front guy on New York's No. 1 power-play unit, so while he's unlikely to ever sniff 50 goals again, he should continue to provide solid offensive production moving forward.

Trocheck was his usual steady self in his first season with the Rangers in 2022-23, finishing with 22 goals and 64 points while playing in all 82 regular-season games, his highest marks since the 2017-18 campaign with the Panthers. Trocheck spent nearly the entire year as New York's No. 2 center skating alongside Artemi Panarin, and he also saw time on the club's top power-play unit prior to the late-season arrivals of Vladimir Tarasenko and Patrick Kane via trade. With a new coaching staff in place, the Rangers seem committed to giving larger roles to both Alexis Lafreniere and Kaapo Kakko in 2023-24, leaving Trocheck a potential candidate for a dip in playing time, particularly with the man advantage. There's a steady floor here from a fantasy perspective, but Trocheck's ceiling is quite limited.

McNabb's usefulness from a fantasy perspective is essentially limited to formats which value hits and blocks. But if you're someone that plays in such a league, he's a must-roster player. The 32-year-old finished second in the NHL in blocks in 2022-23 (197) while posting 200-plus hits (201) for a fifth time. Offensively, McNabb had 17 points and a plus-17 rating, numbers that won't move the needle, but they won't hurt you, either. McNabb has been fairly durable for a guy that employs a tough, rugged style of play, so invest with confidence if you need help in those areas.

Rielly missed well over a month early in the 2022-23 season with a knee issue and never appeared to fully get back on track upon returning. His final numbers -- 4 goals, 37 points, minus-9 rating, 17 power-play points-- were a far cry from the production (10 goals, 68 points, plus-16 rating, 23 power-play points) we saw in 2021-22. Rielly would appear to be a prime bounce-back candidate this season, but the fact the Leafs signed John Klingberg to a one-year deal in free agency is concerning. Klingberg struggles in most situations other than a man up and it remains to be seen how head coach Sheldon Keefe will deploy his new asset. Rielly's role as the quarterback on Toronto's No. 1 power-play unit is probably safe, but it's a situation worth monitoring.

A chronic back injury cost Stone nearly half the 2022-23 season. He appeared in just 43 regular-season games, managing 17 goals and 38 points over that span. He returned for the postseason and didn't show any effects of the ailment, playing in all 22 games in Vegas' run to the Stanley Cup Championship while averaging better than a point-per-game (11 goals, 24 points) in the process. There have been rumblings that the back issue is something Stone will have to manage the rest of his career. He's a lock to produce when in the lineup, but the Golden Knights captain seems likely to receive regular rest even when healthy, making him a risky, but high-upside play in fantasy circles for 2023-24.

For quite a while, Crouse was known as a guy that provided plenty of hits and not much else to fantasy rosters. Last year, however, the offensive light bulb seemed to go off for him at age 25. Crouse set new career-best marks in goals (24), assists (21), points (45), shots on goal (151) and power-play points (8). He also finished with at least 151 hits (194) for a fifth straight year. Crouse's 15.9 shooting percentage was high, but it was roughly in line with what we saw from him in 2021-22. He could continue that success while being leaned upon heavily in 2023-24 by an Arizona team still finding its footing.

Rakell's first full season with the Penguins was a rousing success in 2022-23. He played in all 82 regular-season games, posting 28 goals and 60 points, his highest marks since the 2017-18 campaign. Rakell's 21 power-play points were also a new career-high. The Swede has always been an underrated source of secondary scoring. He shoots the puck a ton (244 shots last year) and compliments high-end players well. Toss in roughly 100 hits and you have a valuable fantasy pick who should be available in the mid-to-late rounds of this year's drafts.

Reichel was unquestionably one of Chicago's best players in 2022-23, but with the team in full-on tank mode (it worked out), they had him spend most of the year in the AHL, where he was dominant (20 goals, 51 points in 55 games). He added 15 points in 23 games with the Blackhawks. In 2023-24, however, Reichel will be unleashed. He's not the same level of prospect as Connor Bedard, but Reichel, who will play this entire season at age 21, is a sneaky late-round re-draft pick and an exceptional keeper/dynasty asset. Don't forget about him on draft day, especially in deeper leagues.

Bouchard's point totals in 2022-23 (eight goals, 40 points in 82 games) was down slightly from his 2021-22 campaign (12 goals, 43 points in 81 games), but it's important to note how much Bouchard improved following the trade of Tyson Barrie to Nashville in late February. Playoffs included, Bouchard posted nine goals and 36 points in his final 33 games. He is the unquestioned quarterback of what is by far the best power-play unit in the NHL, giving Bouchard the potential to post career-best numbers this year.

Aho had a strange season in 2022-23. A good portion of his numbers (36 goals, 218 shots on goal, 16.5 percent shooting percentage) were right in line with what we saw from him two campaigns ago, but his point total dipped significantly from 81 two years ago to 67 last year due to his lack of production with the man advantage. He managed just 15 power-play points last season on the heels of posting 28 in 2021-22. The dip was surprising considering Aho averaged 3:12 of ice time per game a man up last campaign, a new career-best mark. Power-play scoring can fluctuate from year-to-year, making Aho a potential buy-low target in fantasy drafts this fall if you feel he is due for some positive regression in that area.

Dunn's potential breakout failed to materialize during the Kraken's expansion season in 2021-22, but fantasy managers that went back to the well in 2022-23 were rewarded in a major way. Dunn played in 81 of Seattle's 82 regular-season games last year, finishing with 14 goals and 64 points, shattering his previous career-best marks in both categories. Dunn also posted a plus-28 rating on the heels of finishing with a minus-21 rating a year prior. Dunn's power-play production  (0 goals, 15 assists) was somewhat underwhelming considering he averaged 2:49 worth of ice time with the man advantage per game last season, leaving hope that there could be room for a bit more production in that area in 2023-24. Either way, Dunn projects as a solid No. 2 fantasy defender in all formats heading into the upcoming campaign.

Savard played in 62 games in his second season in Montreal in 2022-23, the same number as his first with the team in 2021-22. His offensive totals (three goals, 20 points) were nearly identical for a second straight campaign, and Savard averaged 22:23 worth of playing time per game, his highest mark since the 2015-16 season. Savard's biggest contribution to fantasy rosters lies in the hits and blocks categories. His 61 hits last season were a new career low, and his 176 blocks were a new career high. Ideally, you can find a player that offers a bit more all-around production than Savard when trying to strengthen those categories on draft day.

With virtually every other team around the league seemingly hampered by the salary cap, the Hurricanes have continued to add quality players to their lineup, the latest being Bunting on a three-year, $13.5 million deal this offseason. The former Maple Leaf is fresh off a season in which he tallied 23 goals for a second straight year while adding 174 shots on goal, 10 power-play points, 85 hits and a plus-21 rating for good measure. Bunting isn't a star, but he's an ideal middle-six support piece for a contending club and should be well worth his contract over the course of the next few seasons.

It would be a stretch to say Seider suffered through a "sophomore slump" in 2022-23, but his numbers did take a small step backwards (5 goals, 42 points, 140 shots, 15 power-play points) compared to his Calder Trophy winning 2021-22 campaign (7 goals, 50 points, 187 shots, 21 power-play points). On a more positive note, Seider picked up 207 hits and 190 blocks last year, giving him a massive bump in formats which reward those categories. Seider won't turn 23 until next April and he's locked into his role as Detroit's No. 1 defender, so his fantasy value will remain high in 2023-24, but there's a chance the offensive figures we saw from him in his rookie year represents his ceiling from that standpoint.

A few minor ailments along with the passing of his father limited Ovechkin to 73 games in 2022-23, but he still posted 40 goals for the thirteenth time in his storied career. "The Great 8" added 294 shots on goal, 25 power-play points and 188 hits, so in other words, it was a typical Ovechkin year. Along the way, Ovi passed Gordie Howe for second place all time in goals scored. He'll begin the year with 822 career tallies, 72 behind Wayne Gretzky. Betting on a 38-year-old is typically a terrible strategy from a fantasy standpoint, but we learned long ago to never doubt Ovechkin. A dip in production may come eventually, but it hasn't yet and there are no signs it will arrive in 2023-24.

Tolvanen had some nice moments over the course of four seasons with the Predators, but he struggled with consistency and the team eventually pulled the plug in mid-December of 2022, placing him on waivers. The Kraken quickly pounced and were rewarded with fringe top-six production the rest of the way -- Tolvanen tallied 16 goals and 27 points in 48 games with Seattle last year. The Finn offers very little defensively, but few players in the NHL can shoot the puck like Tolvanen. He should be considered a mid-round fantasy asset that possesses additional value and upside in formats which place an emphasis on goals scored.

Keller's offensive breakout in 2022-23 was the best development for an Arizona team that again found itself among the worst in the league. The Missouri native set career-best marks in goals (37), assists (49), points (86), shots on goal (223) and power-play points (20). It's worth noting that Keller's 16.6 shooting percentage was also a career high, so don't be surprised if his production falls off some in 2023-24. That said, the Coyotes have no option but to give Keller all the minutes he can handle, meaning there should be a steady floor here from a fantasy standpoint. 30 goals and 70 points feels like a fair prediction in terms of Keller's floor this year.

Roy appeared in all 82 games for the Kings last year, posting nine goals and 26 points, new career-best marks. His average playing time, however, was down more than two minutes (18:47) compared to the 2021-22 campaign (20:59). He added 272 combined hits/blocks and a solid, if unspectacular, plus-eight rating. He's locked into a top-six role with LA, but with Drew Doughty still around, Vladislav Gavrikov re-signed and high-end prospect Brandt Clarke on the way, Roy's playing time could further dwindle in 2023-24.

No player in the NHL has been a more consistent source of hits over the course of nearly a decade than Gudas. The 2022-23 season marked the second straight time and the third time in his career in which Gudas posted 300-plus hits (312). He added 124 blocks for good measure. Gudas is never good for more than 15-20 points, but that's not why you're drafting him. He signed a three-year, $12 million deal with Anaheim as a free agent in July. The hits and blocks will follow Gudas to the West Coast, just keep in mind a poor plus-minus rating is likely for the vet since he'll be playing for what projects to be one of the league's weaker teams.

Kempe was just one of 19 players to reach the 40-goal mark in 2022-23, finishing with a career-high 41 tallies. Kempe's 250 shots on goal, 20 power-play points, 119 hits and plus-22 rating were also new high-water marks. The Swede is at risk of some regression in 2023-24 due to his high 16.4 shooting percentage from a year ago, but his role on LA's top line and top power-play unit are secure, giving Kempe a stable fantasy floor. Kempe's assist totals will never be very high -- he had a career-high 26 last season -- so he has more value in formats which place extra emphasis on goals scored, but Kempe still makes for a strong early-to-mid-round pick in all fantasy formats.

Larkin tied his career-best mark with 32 goals in 2022-23, and his 79 points (in 80 games) were a new high-water mark. Larkin's jump in overall production directly correlated to an increased role with the man advantage. He finished with 16 goals and 31 points on the power play - he had never previously posted more than 15 power-play points in a season. Fresh off signing a new eight-year, $69.6 million deal with the Red Wings in March, Larkin could easily crack the point-per-game pace in 2023-24 following Detroit's addition of Alex DeBrincat, who should flank Larkin on Detroit's No. 1 line this year.

There was a debate prior to last season as to whether Pionk or Josh Morrissey was the fantasy defender to have in Winnipeg. Well, we got our answer, and it wasn't Neal. It should be noted Pionk by no means had a bad year. He played in all 82 regular-season games, scoring a career-high 10 goals while posting 30-plus points (33) for the fourth time in five years. Where Pionk really saw a decrease in production was with the man advantage. He picked up just three power-play points last year after finishing with double digits in that category for four straight seasons. It's an open debate as to whether Morrissey will continue to play at a Norris Trophy level, but Pionk should be considered a bit of a gamble either way on draft day.

He wasn't talked about much, but Durzi was a useful late-round fantasy defender last year. In 72 games with LA, he finished with nine goals and 38 points including 16 with the man advantage. Seeking to create cap space to acquire Pierre-Luc Dubois from Winnipeg, the Kings traded Durzi to Arizona in late June. It's a high-end landing spot from a fantasy standpoint, as Durzi should quarterback the Coyotes' No. 1 power-play unit while receiving all the minutes he can handle on a rebuilding club. Just keep in mind a potentially awful plus-minus rating could follow.

After posting 20 assists in his first 135 NHL games, Miller upped that number to 34 (plus nine goals) in 79 games last season. The only three games he missed were due to suspension. In addition to his increasing offensive upside, Miller has posted no fewer than 151 hits over the past two campaigns while averaging about 100 blocks per season. Miller's fantasy ceiling is somewhat limited because he rarely sees power-play time, but he's a legitimate multi-category producer on a good team.

Terry's goal scoring numbers were way down in 2022-23 (23 goals, 61 points in 70 games) compared to two years ago (37 goals, 67 points in 75 games), which was simply the result of his shooting percentage normalizing from 19.3 in 2021-22 to 12.2 percent last season. Of course, he was probably still Anaheim's best player. The Ducks rewarded Terry for his efforts with a seven-year, $49 million deal in August. It would be nice if he played for a better team, but Terry should once again score around 30 goals in addition to double-digit power-play points, making him a mid-round option in all formats.

Among all the breakout performances in the NHL in 2022-23, Verhaeghe's may have been the most impressive. He finished tied for ninth in the league in goals scored with 42, alongside three guys you may have heard of -- Alex Ovechkin, Nathan MacKinnon and Mark Scheifele. Verhaeghe fired 275 shots on goal after posting no more than 167 over the course of his first three NHL seasons. His 73 points were also 18 more than his previous high-water mark. Perhaps the most remarkable thing of all was the fact Verhaeghe did all this with limited power-play production. He had just 7 goals and 13 points with the man advantage last year. Verhaeghe has obviously proven to be capable of surprising us in the past, but fantasy managers would be wise to temper expectations a bit in 2023-24.

Cooley appeared ticketed for a return to the University of Minnesota as recently as late July, but he had a change of heart and ended up signing his entry-level contract with Arizona in July. That's likely the best result for all parties involved. Cooley posted 22 goals and 60 points in 39 games during his freshman campaign with the Gophers, making it obvious that he didn't have much left to learn at the collegiate level. Cooley is one of the top prospects in the league and would probably be the favorite for rookie of the year in 2023-24 if it weren't for that Bedard fella in Chicago. Roughly 20 goals and 60 points with an ugly plus-minus rating seems like a fair first-year projection for Cooley.

Marchessault has had a remarkable career for an undrafted player. His crowning moment came following the end of last season, when he won the Conn Smythe Trophy as the most valuable player in the playoffs following a run which saw him post 13 goals and 25 points in 22 games in helping Vegas win the Stanley Cup. His regular season wasn't too shabby, either. Marchessault scored 25-plus goals (28) for the fifth time in seven years in 2022-23, while his 57 points marked the fourth time in six seasons he's reached that plateau. Toss in about 15 power-play points and well over 200 shots on goal and you have a multi-category, mid-round fantasy asset on your hands.

Splitting the year between Chicago and Dallas, Domi had his best season in ages in 2022-23. His 20 goals and 56 points were his most since the 2018-19 campaign with Montreal, and his 19 points with the man advantage were a new career high. Domi wanted to play for the Maple Leafs and accepted a one-year, $3 million deal in order to make it happen. Both parties appear interested in a longer-term commitment, but this was the best Toronto could do given the team's salary cap situation. Domi is worthy of a late-round fantasy pick regardless, but his ultimate value will be determined in training camp when who he'll be playing with becomes clearer.

Proving his 2021-22 breakout performance was legitimate, Hagel took his game to new heights in 2022-23. He set career-best marks in goals (30), assists (34), points (64), shots on goal (178) and plus-minus rating (plus-23). At the heart of Hagel's bump in scoring was a significantly increased role with the man advantage. He posted 13 power-play points while averaging 2:21 of ice time per game with the man advantage last year. That's compared to just six points and 1:29 of power-play ice time per game a year prior. Consider him a desirable secondary scoring option with upside when hitting the middle rounds of this year's drafts.

In what would end up being his only full season in Calgary, Toffoli was one of the very few Flames that played well in 2022-23. He set career-best marks in goals (37), assists (39), points (73), shots on goal (268) and power-play points (25). Clearly not confident they could extend Toffoli-- who has one year remaining on his contract before being eligible to hit unrestricted free agency -- Calgary dealt him to New Jersey in July in exchange for Yegor Sharangovich and a third-round pick. Even if Toffoli doesn't stay with the Devils long term, he's a clear-cut buy in fantasy leagues for the upcoming season, as playing alongside the likes of Jack Hughes, Nico Hischier and Timo Meier should only serve to enhance his production.

McCann was one of six players to finish with exactly 40 goals in 2022-23. The other five? Auston Matthews, Matthew Tkachuk, Kirill Kaprizov, William Nylander and Timo Meier. McCann's 70 points, 210 shots on goal and plus-18 rating were also new career-best marks. There would appear to be some regression coming in the goals-scored department considering McCann posted a 19 shooting percentage last year after posting a number no higher than 15.1 percent in his first seven NHL seasons, but he's locked into a top-line role on a sneakily good offensive team, meaning the 27-year-old Canadian should be able to carve out mid-round fantasy value again in 2023-24.

Panarin's disappearing act was a driving force behind the Rangers' loss to New Jersey in seven games in Round 1 of the playoffs last year, but he was his usual stellar self in the regular season, posting 90-plus points (92) for a second straight season. In fact, Panarin has cracked the 90-point barrier in three of four seasons with New York, and the year he didn't was the COVID-shortened 2020-21 campaign. Panarin is a true unicorn. He's undersized, but he almost never loses a battle for the puck. Toss in the fact he has 73 points with the man advantage over the course of the past two campaigns and you have a player that remains a rock-solid option on draft day.

McAvoy missed the first month of the 2022-23 season due to offseason shoulder surgery, but he returned in mid-November and sat out just two games the rest of the way. He cracked the 50-point plateau (52) for a second straight season despite sharing time on Boston's No. 1 power-play unit with Hampus Lindholm. Overall, McAvoy's ice time dipped from a whopping 24:40 per night in 2021-22 to 22:18 in 2022-23, but he still contributed north of 200 combined hits/blocks (215) despite the missed time and reduced role. Still just 25 years of age, McAvoy projects as a multi-category contributor and a low-end No. 1 fantasy defender this year.

Jack Eichel was arguably Vegas' best player in the team's run to a Stanley Cup Championship in 2022-23. Thankfully for Buffalo, Tuch was one of the assets the team received in return when Eichel was shipped to Sin City in November of 2021. Tuch, a native of upstate New York, is coming off a season in which he posted new career-best marks in goals (36), assists (43), points (79), shots on goal (218), power play points (20) and average ice time (19:09) despite missing eight games late in the season with a lower-body issue. Tuch may be due for some minor regression due to his 16.9 shooting percentage from a year ago, but he's locked into a top-line role for an improving young Sabres team, so similar numbers to what we saw in 2022-23 should be well within reach in 2023-24.

Those hoping for top-tier production from Ekblad a season ago came away disappointed. He finished with just 38 points in 71 games, a far cry from the 57 points in 61 games we saw from him in 2021-22. Ekblad was banged up for a good portion of the season and lost key offensive minutes to the emerging Brandon Montour along the way. Ekblad played through a broken foot and an oblique tear in the playoffs before undergoing offseason shoulder surgery. He's not expected to be ready for training camp, although it remains unclear if he's in danger of missing regular-season games. Given the injury concerns and the presence of Montour, the risk may outweigh the potential reward with Ekblad from a fantasy perspective for 2023-24.

Buoyed by a career-high 20.4 shooting percentage, Scheifele finished with 42 goals in 81 games last season, his most to date in any one year. On the other hand, his point total (68) and plus-minus rating (minus-16) left much to be desired. Scheifele played just 1:40 in Winnipeg's Game 4 loss to Vegas in Round 1 of the playoffs and ended up sitting out Game 5 -- Winnipeg's final game of the season -- with what was deemed an upper-body injury, but the ailment isn't considered a long-term concern. Set to become an unrestricted free agent in the summer of 2024, Scheifele's name may appear in trade rumors all season, especially if the Jets get off to a slow start. Keep that in mind on draft day.

Prior to the 2022-23 campaign, Karlsson managed 27 goals and 142 points in 211 games in his prior four seasons combined. He finished last season with 25 goals and 101 points in 82 games, becoming the first defensemen since Brian Leetch in 1991-92 to crack the century mark. It was a magical year on numerous fronts that culminated in a Norris Trophy, but it's almost certainly unsustainable. Karlsson's 12 percent shooting percentage was by far the highest of his career, while his minus-30 rating was his worst mark since the 2010-11 season. Karlsson was moved in August, being traded to the Penguins. As a result, his plus-minus rating should improve in 2023-24, but his offensive numbers, which will almost certainly still be great, will likely drop significantly. Karlsson should be viewed as a No. 1 fantasy rearguard in all formats, but don't expect 100-plus points again.

A part-time player over the course of his first four years in the NHL, Forsling has not only been a regular for Florida over the past two seasons, but a good one. He played in all 82 games for the club in 2022-23, tallying a career-high 13 goals and 41 points. Forsling added 209 shots on goal and a plus-19 rating for good measure. As well as he's played of late, Forsling remains a bit of a risky fantasy bet simply because he doesn't receive much power-play time. The 1:20 of ice time per game with the man advantage he averaged last season was his most to date and it only resulted in five power-play points. There's a steady floor here, but the upside is pretty limited.

Maccelli was brilliant in his first full year in the league in 2022-23, leading all rookies in assists (38) while finishing second in scoring (49 points in 64 games) among first-year players, trailing only Calder Trophy winner Matty Beniers of Seattle. He was named to the NHL All-Rookie team as a result. Maccelli spent two seasons playing in Finland's top league before arriving in North America, so he had plenty of experience going up against older opposition before debuting for Arizona. His offensive output looks sustainable, particularly when you factor in Maccelli's guaranteed significant role on one of the weakest teams in the NHL. Don't forget about the 2019 fourth-round pick in the latter stages of your fantasy draft.

Regression hit Mangiapane in a major way in 2022-23 and fantasy managers paid for it as a result. Fresh off a 2021-22 campaign which saw him post 35 goals in 82 games on the strength of an inflated 18.9 shooting percentage, Mangiapane saw his shooting percentage drop to an abnormally low 9.3 in 2022-23 and the result was an underwhelming 17 goals. Mangiapane also ran into some bad luck with the man advantage, managing just four power-play points despite averaging a career-best 2:05 worth of ice time per night a man up. As is generally the case, the truth likely lies somewhere in the middle. Mangiapane certainly isn't a 35-goal scorer in a typical year, but the advanced numbers suggest he's due for a bounce back in 2023-24, making him a late-round fantasy option in most formats.

Now 34-years-old, the days of Shattenkirk being a high-end fantasy asset have come and gone. He managed just 27 points in 75 games for Anaheim in 2022-23, adding a minus-20 rating while playing for one of the worst defensive teams in NHL history. Shattenkirk entered unrestricted free agency this summer, ultimately agreeing to a one-year, $1 million deal with the Bruins. It's a strong bet for the team as Shattenkirk still moves the puck well and commands plenty of respect in the locker room, but it's hard to see him producing enough to be worthy of anything more than a late-round selection this year's fantasy drafts.

Proving his 2021-22 breakout (21 goals, 64 points, 14 power-play points) was no fluke, Stephenson scored at nearly an identical clip (sixteen goals, 65 points, 15 power-play points) last year. He was strictly used as a bottom-six depth player during his days in Washington, but he's displayed an ability to fill a top-six role with Vegas when necessary. The biggest concern regarding Stephenson's fantasy outlook moving forward is the fact he doesn't shoot the puck much. He has just 245 shots on goal in his last 160 games, a shockingly low number for a player that has been scoring at Stephenson's pace. Keep that in mind on draft day.

Kadri picked a great time for a career year, as the 27 goals and 87 points in 71 games he posted back in 2021-22 paved the way for a shiny seven-year, $49 million deal with the Flames. He was nowhere near as effective in his first year in Calgary in 2022-23, seeing his numbers plummet to 24 goals and 56 points in 82 games. While Kadri was a massive disappointment, it's worth noting his final numbers were right in line with what we've seen from him most of his career, with his final season in Colorado being the major outlier. There's a steady floor here from a fantasy standpoint, just don't expect Kadri to threaten the point-per-game clip in 2023-24.

The Kings acquired Fiala in a trade from the Wild in the summer of 2022 and were rewarded with more than a point-per-game pace (72 points in 69 games) in his first season with the club. He missed time late in the year and early in the playoffs with a lower-body issue, but he returned prior to the Kings' elimination from the postseason. Fiala's 24 points with the man advantage last year were a new career high, while most of his secondary numbers were similar to what we saw in his final year with Minnesota in 2021-22. Still just 26 years of age, Fiala should once again be good for roughly 30 goals and 70-plus points in 2023-24.

Aaron Ekblad was the Panther defender that cost a pretty penny in drafts a year ago, but it was Montour who emerged from the pack with by far the most fantasy value. He finished with 73 points in 80 games, a number that tied him for fifth among all NHL rearguards in scoring. Montour added 33 points with the man advantage after posting just 30 in his first six NHL seasons combined. Toss in 242 shots on goal, 107 penalty minutes, a plus-nine rating and 185 combined hits/blocks and you have a legitimate high-end fantasy asset on your hands. Montour underwent offseason shoulder surgery and it's not clear if he'll be ready for the start of the season, so keep that in mind on draft day, but 29-year-old should go right back to his point-producing ways upon returning to the lineup.

Gostisbehere's production dipped a bit last season, but he was still plenty valuable. In a year split between Arizona and Carolina, the man they call "Ghost" tallied 13 goals and 41 points in 75 games. 15 of those points came with the man advantage. Gostisbehere struggles when tasked with logging heavy defensive minutes, but teams know that by now. He signed a one-year deal with the Red Wings in July worth a shade over $4 million. He'll enter a potentially fantasy-friendly situation in 2023-24 assuming he can earn a spot on Detroit's top power-play unit.

Never known for his offense, Mayfield played in all 82 games for the Islanders last season, setting new career-best marks in both goals (six) and points (24) in addition to averaging north of 21 minutes of ice time (21:02) per game. Clearly feeling they would be unable to replace him if he left via unrestricted free agency, New York handed Mayfield a new seven-year, $24.5 million contract this summer. It pays Mayfield like a middle-pairing defender, which he probably is, at least for the Islanders. From a fantasy perspective, Mayfield offers little upside. Even the 275 combined hits/blocks he posted last season were essentially negated by his lack of production elsewhere.

A late February trade from St. Louis to Vegas ended up being a huge boon for Barbashev. He fit in seamlessly in a top-line role with the Golden Knights, posting 16 points in 23 regular-season games before adding 18 points in 22 postseason contests, helping the Knights win the Stanley Cup. Recognizing a great situation when he saw it, Barbashev signed a new five-year, $25 million deal to stay with Vegas in late June. The trio of Barbashev, Jack Eichel and Jonathan Marchessault was so great in the playoffs that it would be shocking to see head coach Bruce Cassidy break them up for the start of the 2023-24 campaign. Barbashev is worth a long look in the mid-to-late rounds of this year's drafts.

Iafallo established himself as a reasonable middle-six depth player over the last few seasons to the point the Kings were able to make him a key cog in the deal which brought Pierre-Luc Dubois to LA in late June. Iafallo posted 14 goals and 36 points in 59 games a season ago and would have set new career-best marks across the board had he not missed six weeks early in the year with a lower-body issue. Iafallo is a plug-and-play guy for Winnipeg and a candidate for an increased role with his new club, although 20 goals and 50 points would seem to be about the ceiling here from an offensive standpoint.

Vatrano has always been an underrated goal scorer with an excellent shot. Some thought a breakout performance was possible in his first year with a weak Anaheim team in 2022-23, but his numbers (22 goals, 41 points, 231 shots on goal, nine power-play points) while solid, were right in line with what we have seen from him in the past. Toss in Vatrano's ugly minus-29 rating, and he was essentially unusable from a fantasy standpoint in leagues that count that statistic. His plus-minus rating may improve some, and the scoring output should still be there, but you can probably find a player with more upside on draft day.

Playing in all 82 games for Montreal for a second straight season, Suzuki led the Canadiens with 66 points last year, a whopping 28 more than any of his teammates. His minus-13 rating was also a considerably better number than the minus-29 mark we saw from him in 2021-22. Toss in 17 points with the man advantage, and Suzuki had a strong fantasy year. It could have been that much better had running mate Cole Caufield not gone down in mid-January with a shoulder injury which ended his season. How much upside Suzuki has on what should continue to be a middling club in the Habs is up for debate, but he would appear to be a lock for at least 25 goals and 60 points if healthy due to his massive role as Montreal's No. 1 center.

Kuzmenko's 2022-23 rookie season was baffling. He scored 39 goals, a number higher than even the most optimistic of projections. That said, Kuzmenko's shooting percentage was 27.3. To give you an idea of how high a number that is, among all players that averaged at least one shot per game played, Tampa Bay's Brayden Point was second at 21.7 percent. Kuzmenko added 35 assists and had 19 points with the man advantage, so he helped in some other categories, but there's almost certainly some harsh regression forthcoming in 2023-24. That makes Kuzmenko, who signed a two-year, $11 million extension in January, more of a mid-to-late round fantasy option than an early-to-mid rounder in 2023-24.

It seems not all that long ago that DeBrusk requested a trade from the Bruins. The team never found a deal to its liking, which ended up being a great result for both parties. DeBrusk, who has since rescinded the request, posted a career-high 27 goals, 50 points, 191 shots on goal, 14 power-play points and a plus-26 rating in 2022-23. He also added four tallies and a couple helpers in Boston's brief seven-game playoff run. Patrice Bergeron retired this offseason, and the club has yet to find a decent replacement for the future Hall of Famer. On the bright side, that could lead to DeBrusk being locked into a spot on the Bruins' top power-play unit in 2023-24, a gig that should lead to ample fantasy value.

Graves completed his second and final season with the Devils in 2022-23, posting nearly identical offensive numbers (8 goals, 26 points in 78 games) as his first campaign with the team. His plus-minus rating (plus-34) was stellar, and Graves added new career-best marks in both shots on goal (141) and blocks (152). The Penguins were clearly impressed with what they saw, handing Graves a six-year, $27 million deal to lure him from their division rival this offseason. He'll undoubtedly help Pittsburgh win hockey games over the next half decade, but Graves' fantasy value will continue to be limited in formats that don't reward hits and blocks.

McCabe has been a steady, stay-at-home defender for years now. Last season, split between Chicago and Toronto, he started to add a bit more offense to his game. McCabe finished with a career-high 25 points, 96 shots on goal and plus-19 rating. He was also good for 300-plus combined hits/blocks for a second straight campaign. You shouldn't draft McCabe in in search of point production but playing the entirety of the upcoming campaign in Toronto should serve to boost him in that area, and he should once again deliver elite hit/block totals.

Orlov is another player that picked a great time for a career-best year. He began the season in Washington before being dealt to Boston.
