He missed a month starting in mid-November with a lower-body issue, but he was otherwise healthy. Appearing in 66 games, Orlov set new high-water marks in points (36) and power-play points (eight) while tying a career best in hits with 137. He signed a two-year, $15.5 deal with Carolina as a free agent in July. Orlov should continue to put up his fair share of points along with posting a terrific plus-minus rating with his new club, but the presence of Brent Burns and Tony DeAngelo figures to limit his playing time with the man advantage.

There's a real case to be made that Pastrnak was the best player in the NHL not named Connor McDavid in 2022-23. He was the only player other than McDavid to receive a first-place vote for MVP, and his 61 goals placed him second in the NHL only behind McDavid. Pastrnak's 113 points were a new career-high, and his 407 shots on goal were 41 more than any other skater. He was rewarded with a new eight-year, $90 million contract extension in March. It's a stretch to forecast back-to-back 60-goal campaigns from any player, but Pastrnak should easily flirt with 50 tallies if he remains healthy. He's an easy first-round pick in all formats.

Hughes came very close to cracking the point-per-game mark for the first time in his career last season, finishing with seven goals and 76 points in 78 games. His seven tallies were especially admirable considering he scored just once in his first 35 games. As expected, Hughes did most of his damage with the man advantage. His 34 points a man up tied Hughes with Miro Heiskanen of the Stars for most in the league among defenders. Hughes' hit/block totals were very low for a rearguard (100 combined last season), but this type of offensive production is nearly impossible to find from the back end. Hughes should continue to provide eye-popping offensive totals while disappointing in the hit and block categories in 2023-24.

Chabot is coming off one of his best seasons to date and it could have been even better had he not missed five games around Thanksgiving with a concussion and Ottawa's final eight games of the year with a broken wrist. All told, Chabot posted 11 goals and 41 points in 68 games in 2022-23. His 20 power-play points were a new career-best mark, and he chipped in 79 hits and 123 blocks for good measure. The main concern regarding Chabot's fantasy value now is the presence of Jakob Chychrun. Acquired from Arizona late in the year, like Chabot, Chychrun is an offensive-minded defender. Both are left-handed shots, so it seems unlikely that the Senators will deploy both on their No. 1 power-play unit. It's a situation worth closely monitoring in training camp.

Few players in the NHL are as consistent as Lee. His numbers won't blow you away, but you can set your clock by his production. The Notre Dame product played in all 82 games for the Islanders in 2022-23, posting 28 goals for a second straight year. His 14 points with the man advantage and 125 hits were also right in line with his usual numbers. How much fantasy value Lee has is dependent on your format. His assist totals are always low - he's never had more than 23 in a single season - so it's up for you to decide how much his goal totals, middling power-play production and solid hit numbers are worth on draft day.

Those that rolled the dice on Malkin in fantasy drafts in 2022-23 were handsomely rewarded. Seemingly constantly injured, the big man played in all 82 games for Pittsburgh last year. The result was 27 goals and 83 points, his highest totals since the 2018-19 campaign. The durability was shocking considering Malkin had appeared in 70-plus games just once in the previous decade. So, where does that leave us moving forward? Common sense dictates Malkin is unlikely to make it through another full season healthy, but he's shown he's still a point-per-game player despite the fact he will play this season at age 36. Take that into account before you take the plunge on draft day.

Tavares came out of seemingly nowhere to post 36 goals and 80 points in 80 games for the Maple Leafs last season, his highest marks since the 2018-19 campaign, his first in Toronto. Tavares' 39 power-play points in 2022-23 were the most of his career, tying him for sixth overall in the league. Toss in 277 shots on goal and 110 hits, and you have a legitimate high-end, multi-category fantasy producer. Tavares, who will be 33 by Opening Night, is obviously a worse bet moving forward than teammates Auston Matthews, Mitch Marner and William Nylander, but there appears to be considerably more gas left in the tank for Tavares now when compared to this time last year.

Carlson was struck in the face with a puck during a game against Winnipeg two days before Christmas and his 2022-23 season was derailed as a result. He ended up missing nearly three months before returning for Washington's final 10 games in what was ultimately a lost year. Carlson did manage eight points upon returning, so at least he appeared to be fully healthy at that point. The Capitals will be running it back with essentially the same aging roster we saw a year ago, so Carlson's role as the No. 1 defensive option on the team's top power-play unit isn't in doubt. The injury last season was due to a fluke play, making Carlson an obvious buy-low candidate should he slip in fantasy drafts this fall.

In his first season as captain of the Rangers, Trouba was again solid from a fantasy standpoint in 2022-23. He posted eight goals, 30 points (five with the man advantage), 199 shots on goal and a plus-seven rating in 82 games. Trouba's 218 hits and 196 blocks were also both career-best marks. His power-play production may dry up a bit this year, as the Rangers already have Adam Fox to run their top unit and added Erik Gustafsson to the mix in free agency, but Trouba remains an elite source of hits and blocks, and he'll also add some secondary scoring and a reasonable plus-minus rating. That equates to significant fantasy value depending on your format.

Hughes made a mockery of the NCAA in his second season at the University of Michigan in 2022-23, averaging more than a point-per-game (10 goals, 48 points in 39 games). He was never expected to play a third year of collegiate hockey, and he ended up signing with the Devils before joining the club late last season. He scored an overtime winner in his second NHL game before being in the lineup consistently in the postseason. Hughes has as much natural ability as any rearguard that's enter the league in a long time. The presence of Dougie Hamilton and the fact Hughes will play the entire 2023-24 season at age 20 will likely result in growing pains from a fantasy perspective, but he possesses the type of talent you want to bet on, especially long term.

Many Devils players had career-best years during the team's 2022-23 breakout season, with Hischier, their captain, leading the charge. The former No. 1 overall pick (2017) set new high-water marks in goals (31), assists (49), points (80), plus-minus rating (plus-33), and power-play points (19). It's a very positive sign that Hischier was able to notch 30-plus goals in a year in which his shooting percentage (12.1 percent) was considerably lower than the previous two seasons. There are a lot of mouths to feed in the New Jersey offense, but Hischier is ensured a top-line, top power-play role on one of the league's best young teams, making him a rock-solid fantasy pick on draft day.

The No. 1 overall selection in the 2022 draft, Slafkovsky began the 2022-23 season in Montreal as an 18-year-old. He had a couple nice moments, but he failed to make a consistent impact before suffering a mid-January lower-body injury which ended his season. All told, Slafkovsky had four goals and 10 points in 39 games. It'd be nice if all top draft picks immediately produced at the level of Connor McDavid and Auston Matthews, but that simply isn't reality. Nonetheless, it wouldn't be surprising to see a breakout campaign from Slafkovsky in 2023-24, potentially making him worth the gamble in the middle rounds of this year's drafts.

If you're looking for consistency, Schmaltz is your man. He racked up 22 goals and 58 points in 63 games in 2022-23, this on the heels of a 23-goal, 59-point performance in 63 games a year prior. The pessimistic view here would be that Schmaltz has missed 38 games over the past two years. He has 20 power-play points over that same span and has somehow managed to finish with a positive plus-minus rating each year despite playing for one of the worst teams in the NHL, so there's legitimate fantasy potential here if Schmaltz can somehow make it through the 2023-24 campaign unscathed.

Batherson missed a huge chunk of time in the 2021-22 season due a serious ankle injury, but he bounced back to play in all 82 games for Ottawa a year ago. He finished with career-best marks in goals (22), assists (40), points (62), shots on goal (249) and power-play points (29). The most remarkable thing of all is that Batherson's season should have been considerably better than it was. His 8.8 shooting percentage was shockingly low compared to the 15.5 and 15.3 percent marks we saw from him in the two years prior. There's legitimate 30-goal, 70-point upside here. Don't forget about Batherson on draft day.

Depending on the format of your league, there's a real case to make that Tkachuk is worthy of a top-five selection. Not only did he average more than a point-per-game (35 goals, 83 points in 82 games) for the first time in his career in 2022-23, but he also finished with 240-plus hits (242) for a fourth straight year. Toss in new high-water marks in shots on goal (347) and power-play points (29), and you have an elite all-around fantasy producer on your hands. Don't be afraid to reach for Tkachuk on draft day if your league values those secondary statistics beyond the scoring.

On a team full of stars, Nylander was arguably Toronto's most important player in 2022-23. He scored 40 goals, the first time in his career in which he's reached that plateau, and he also set new career highs in points (87) and shots on goal (293). Nylander was also once again his usual productive self while a man up, adding 28 power-play points. Not only has Nylander proven to be a multi-category fantasy stud, but he's durable, having missed just one regular-season game over the past two seasons combined. The Swede has one more year left on his deal at a shade under $7 million before he'll be eligible to head into unrestricted free agency in the summer of 2024, so expect contract talks to dominate the narrative here until the Leafs and/or Nylander makes a decision on his future.

Simply put, fantasy managers that drafted Hedman to anchor their fantasy team in 2022-23 got burned. He closed with nine goals and 49 points in 76 games, a far cry from the career-best 20 goals and 85 points he posted in 2021-22. The most concerning number of all was Hedman's lack of productivity with the man advantage. His average ice time per game a man up dropped by nearly a minute from 3:35 to 2:36, with the result being a measly 14 power-play points compared to 38 two years ago. There's a case to be made that Hedman is due for some positive regression in 2023-24 considering his shooting percentage last season was just 4.9 percent, his lowest mark in well over a decade, but there appear to be numerous higher-upside targets in drafts this fall.

Logging his first season in Boston following nine-plus years in Anaheim, Lindholm was an absolute revelation for the Bruins in 2022-23. He set new career-best marks in goals (10), assists (43), points (53), shots on goal (158) and power-play points (17). Lindholm also led the league in plus-minus rating with a ridiculous plus-49 rating. The Bruins will almost certainly take a step back as a team in 2023-24, but Lindholm remains locked into a top-four role on one of the NHL's better clubs, meaning another season of mid-round fantasy value is on the horizon. Don't forget about the Swede on draft day.

In a year split between Detroit and Boston, Bertuzzi missed significant time due to a hand injury in 2022-23. He appeared in just 50 games combined between his two stops, posting eight goals and 30 points. He did save his best work for the playoffs, racking up five goals and 10 points in the Bruins' shocking seven-game, first-round playoff loss to Florida. With seemingly no NHL clubs having the cap space to extend long-term deals this offseason, Bertuzzi, a Sudbury, Ontario native, inked a one-year, $5.5 million deal with his hometown Maple Leafs as an unrestricted free agent. It's an exceptional fit on multiple levels, as Bertuzzi's gritty style should mesh well alongside the likes of Auston Matthews and Mitch Marner. The 28-year-old's production in 2023-24 could easily return to the level we saw from him with the Red Wings two years ago (30 goals, 62 points in 68 games).

DeBrincat arrived in Ottawa last season following a half decade with the Blackhawks. His numbers dropped considerably, as he finished with 27 goals and 66 points in 82 games, a far cry from the 41 goals and 78 points in 82 games we saw from him in 2021-22. DeBrincat's dip in production directly correlates with his shooting percentage dipping to 10.3, a number well below his 13.4 percent career mark. The Michigan native made it clear he wasn't interested in inking a new deal with the Senators, so the club dealt him to his hometown Red Wings in July. DeBrincat signed a four-year, $31.5 million extension as part of the trade. DeBrincat may not reach the heights we saw from him in his best days in Chicago, but fantasy managers can expect an improvement on his pedestrian numbers from a year ago in 2023-24.

The Canadiens were really banged up in 2022-23, and Harvey-Pinard took advantage. He got into 34 games with the club, posting 14 goals (and six assists) on the strength of a ridiculous and unsustainable 24.1 shooting percentage. While it was a great story for the 24-year-old Quebec native, the odds of it carrying over to this season are virtually nil. Cole Caufield and Juraj Slafkovsky will be back from injury to reclaim top-six roles, and Alex Newhook was also brought in from Colorado. Nonetheless, Harvey-Pinard likely showed enough last year to earn a long look at a regular role for the Habs in 2023-24.

Jensen's fourth full season in Washington in 2022-23 was a bit of a mixed bag. He set new career-best marks in both assists (24) and points (29 in 77 games), but his plus-minus rating tanked in a major way, dropping from plus-32 in 2021-22 to minus-1 last year. That's what you get when the team you're playing for takes a massive step backwards. Ultimately, Jensen doesn't contribute enough in any one area to be worthy of anything but a late-round fantasy pick. His scoring numbers are mediocre and his combined hit/block totals (225 in 2022-23) while fine are far from elite.

The Devils broke out as a team last season, and they were led by Hughes, their unquestioned MVP. Hughes played the entire year at age 21, posting 43 goals and 99 points (including 31 with the man advantage) in 78 games. Hughes' 336 shots on goal placed him fourth in the league behind only David Pastrnak, Nathan MacKinnon, Connor McDavid and Brady Tkachuk. Everything regarding Hughes' massive breakout campaign appears to be entirely sustainable moving forward. Simply put, there just aren't many NHL players that possess the physical gifts of the No. 1 overall selection in 2019. Hughes deserves to be in the late first-round discussion in fantasy leagues this fall.

Zibanejad has established himself as a legitimate No. 1 center and the 2022-23 campaign represented his most complete to date. He finished with 39 goals and set new career-best marks in assists (52), points (91), shots on goal (251) and power-play points (39). In fact, Zibanejad's production with the man advantage placed him tied for sixth in the league. A do-it-all player that logs a ton of minutes for the Rangers in all situations, Zibanejad has developed into arguably the club's most indispensable forward. Still just 30 years old, Mika makes for an ideal No. 1 fantasy center for those that miss out on the likes of Connor McDavid and Auston Matthews on draft day.

Arguably the best prospect to enter the NHL since Connor McDavid in 2015, all eyes will be on Bedard, the No. 1 overall pick in the 2023 Draft, during the upcoming campaign. Bedard closed his WHL career with 134 goals and 271 points in 134 games spread over three seasons. The expectations for him are going to be out of hand from the very start. To Chicago's credit, the team added a handful of experienced veterans (Taylor Hall, Nick Foligno, Corey Perry) to help Bedard along, but the Blackhawks are still almost certainly going to be one of the worst teams in the league this year. There's a high probability Bedard will be one of the better players in the NHL sooner rather than later, but it may take a season or two for him to reach his full potential. Having said that, 30-35 goals and 80-plus points is still a possibility for Bedard in 2023-24.

The Jets were a much-improved team last season compared to two years ago, but Connor's individual numbers were way down. He managed just 31 goals and 80 points in 82 games, this coming on the heels of a season in which he posted 47 goals and 93 points in 79 games. Connor also posted a career-worst minus-11 rating. On a more positive note, Connor set a new high-water mark in terms of power-play points (29), while his 11.4 shooting percentage was by far his lowest to date, so he should be due for some positive regression in the goals-scored department in 2023-24. One of the few Jets that seems certain to stay with the team long term, Connor remains worthy of an early-round pick on draft day.

Marchand's season debut in 2022-23 was delayed by about two weeks following offseason hip surgery, but he played his first game in late October and missed just two regular-season games the rest of the way, finishing with 21 goals and 67 points in 73 games. Marchand's 21 tallies were his fewest since the strike-shortened 2012-13 campaign, but his secondary stats (74 PIM, 183 shots on goal, 29 power-play points, 81 hits, plus-27 rating) were once again excellent. Patrice Bergeron announced his retirement this summer, which will undoubtedly negatively impact Marchand's fantasy value in 2023-24, but he'll still be serving as Boston's No. 1 left wing. The uncertainty surrounding how much Bergeron's exit will impact Marchand's production this year is a legitimate concern, but he'll likely be worth the gamble on draft day.

Those that reached for Victor Hedman in fantasy leagues last year were burned badly, and those fortunate enough to get Sergachev at a relative discount were rewarded handsomely. The latter had by far his most productive season to date, posting 10 goals and 64 points in 79 games, a number that tied him with Seattle's Vince Dunn for tenth among all NHL defenders in scoring. At the heart of Sergachev's surge was an increased role with the man advantage. He tallied 27 points on the power play last year after managing just 28 power-play points in 204 games over the course of the prior three seasons combined. Hedman isn't going anywhere and that should always be considered when analyzing Sergachev's fantasy potential, but the 25-year-old seems like the Tampa Bay rearguard to have heading into the 2023-24 campaign.

With Meier steaming towards unrestricted free agency, the Sharks cashed in their chips and dealt him to New Jersey in late February. Meier's point total was down with the Devils (14 points in 21 games) compared to his start to the year in San Jose (52 points in 57 games), but he was scoring goals at about the same clip, ultimately finishing with 40 tallies for the first time in his career. Meier's 23 power-play points were a new high-water mark, and he posted 150-plus hits (154) for the third time in four years. The Devils inked Meier to a new eight-year, $70.4 million contract in June, ensuring he will stick in New Jersey for the foreseeable future. It's a great long-term landing spot from a fantasy perspective, as playing alongside guys like Jack Hughes and Nico Hischier should ensure Meier retains early round value.

A pair of significant injuries limited Theodore to just 55 regular-season games in 2022-23. He was predictably effective when healthy (8 goals, 41 points), although his decreased role with the man advantage is a concern moving forward. Theodore averaged just 2:16 worth of power-play time per game last year, his lowest mark in four seasons since arriving in Vegas. His overall ice time was down, as well, from 23:08 per game in 2022-23 to 21:26 last year. The Golden Knights are expected to bring back the same six defenders that helped them win the Stanley Cup last season, meaning Theodore will likely once again split power-play time with Alex Pietrangelo, making Theo more of a floor than a ceiling play from a fantasy standpoint.

Faulk is among the most boring, yet consistently useful defenders in the NHL on a yearly basis. With teammate Torey Krug limited to just 63 games due to a variety of ailments in 2022-23, Faulk took advantage, posting a career-high 50 points while playing in all 82 games for St. Louis. Faulk has averaged north of 23 minutes of ice time per game for three straight seasons while finishing with more than 200 blocks/hits in six of the past seven campaigns. Toss in double-digit power-play points and you have a rearguard worthy of a mid-round fantasy pick in all formats.

The poster boy for poor NHL contracts as recently as a couple years ago, Skinner is coming off his second straight 30 goal (35) season. He finished with a career high in both points (82 in 79 games) and power-play points (21) He also posted a plus-15 rating, a remarkable number considering he was no better than a minus-11 in any of the prior three years. Expecting Skinner to score at better than a point-per-game pace again in 2023-24 is a bit much, but he's still worthy of a mid-round fantasy pick.

Few players in the NHL outperformed expectations to the level we saw from Necas in 2022-23. He played in all 82 games for Carolina, posting career-best marks in goals (28), assists (43), points (71), shots on goal (240) and power-play points (26). Necas averaged 3:03 of playing time per game with the man advantage, a massive increase in usage from the 1:39 he saw nightly in 2021-22. Still just 24 years of age, Necas may cost a pretty penny in fantasy drafts this year, and he'll probably be worth it. He's a mid-round asset in most formats.

Norris was a popular fantasy pick in 2022-23 following a breakout 35-goal performance in 2021-22. But he suffered a shoulder injury in a late October game against Arizona. He returned for three games in mid-January before aggravating the issue and requiring surgery which ended his year. All told, Norris played just eight games last season. As a result, he'll be a prime buy-low opportunity for fantasy managers in drafts this year. Outside of Vladimir Tarasenko subbing in for Alex DeBrincat, the Ottawa forward group will essentially remain unchanged in 2023-24, which means Norris will be in a prime position for a substantial role.

In many respects, Jones's 2022-23 season played out exactly as expected from a fantasy perspective. He played in 72 of 82 games for Chicago, posting reasonable scoring totals (12 goals, 37 points), a boatload of hits (106) and blocks (125), and a truly awful plus-minus rating (minus-38). Unfortunately, it's unlikely that last number will improve in 2023-24, as he'll be logging about 25 minutes per game on one of the league's least-talented teams. The drafting of Connor Bedard and the acquisition of Taylor Hall should help Chicago's power play, boosting Jones' fantasy value, but his desirability will remain limited in formats which take plus-minus rating into account.

Hamilton's first season in New Jersey back in 2021-22 was a struggle. He was banged-up for a good portion of the year and didn't produce much (9 goals, 30 points in 62 games) when healthy. Dougie looked like an obvious buy-low candidate in fantasy drafts last fall and rewarded those who took the plunge. Hamilton set new career-best marks in goals (22), assists (54), points (76), shots on goal (275) and power-play points (28) last year. His 76 points placed him fourth among defensemen behind only Erik Karlsson, Josh Morrissey and Quinn Hughes. The Devils are a team on the rise and Hamilton is their unquestioned No. 1 defensive option, making him a legitimate top-flight fantasy play in all formats in 2023-24.

Those hoping for a full-on breakout from Zegras in his second NHL season didn't get their wish in 2022-23. His offensive numbers (23G, 65P in 81GP) were right in line with what we saw in his 2021-22 rookie campaign, and Zegras' plus-minus rating (minus-24) was once again awful. On a more positive note, Zegras added 17 points with the man advantage and remained healthy. The Ducks are trending in the right direction, but it's likely going to be another few seasons before all their top prospects are ready to contribute. Fantasy managers would be wise not to overpay for Zegras on draft day. He remains more of a solid-floor player than a high-ceiling guy at this point.

With the Coyotes in the midst of another disappointing season, Valimaki took over as the club's No. 1 power-play quarterback last year following the trade of Jakob Chychrun to Ottawa. The increased usage resulted in a career-high 34 points (including a dozen with the man advantage) in 78 games for the 24-year-old. It was a nice ride for anyone lucky enough to grab Valimaki off the waiver wire, just don't expect a repeat performance. Arizona acquired Sean Durzi in a trade from LA and signed Matt Dumba in free agency this offseason, both of whom may supplant Valimaki on the depth chart, so expectations should be tempered.

DeAngelo's lone season in Philadelphia in 2022-23 didn't go very well. He predictably clashed with head coach John Tortorella despite once again putting up strong offensive numbers (11 goals, 42 points in 70 games). The Flyers bought him out of the final year of his deal in mid-July, allowing DeAngelo to sign a one-year contract with Carolina, the team he played for the year prior. Expect Tony D to share time on the club's top power-play unit with veteran Brent Burns, making him a mid-to-late round fantasy selection for those in need of point production and not much else.

Vrana had a tough year in 2022-23. He entered the player assistance program just days into the season and was later waived by the Red Wings in January-he eventually landed with the Blues in March. He finally got on track late in the year, posting five goals and eight points in his final 11 games. Vrana has always been supremely talented. He scored 49 goals in a two-year span with Washington not all that long ago and is still just 27 years old. Nonetheless, he should be viewed as a late-round dart throw with upside in this year's drafts.

Couture played in all 82 games for the Sharks in 2022-23, posting 27 goals and 67 points, his highest numbers since the 2018-19 campaign. His 20 points with the man advantage were also his most since 2017-18. He added a career-high 128 hits, but he also posted a career-worst minus-30 rating. With San Jose seemingly years away from contending, Couture is locked into a major role, giving him a solid fantasy floor, but it's difficult to project any sort of meaningful improvement over last year's numbers considering he'll be playing for a team that will likely find itself near the bottom of the NHL standings in 2023-24.

Arvidsson was a question mark last season due to a serious back injury the year prior, but he appeared in 77 of 82 games for the Kings and was his usual steady self (26 goals, 59 points) in the process. Arvidsson's production was driven by a career-high 25 power-play points, a shocking total considering his average ice time per game with the man advantage was just 2:15 last season, down from 2:37 in 2012-22. Arvidsson has consistently found a way to pile up points, even with limited power-play production, but the expected upcoming regression in that department makes him more of a late-round fantasy pick than a mid-round option.

It was only a one-year deal, but there's a case to be made Klingberg, who was paid $7 million by the Ducks, was the most disappointing free agent signing in the NHL last summer. He ended up splitting the year between Anaheim and Minnesota, posting just 33 points, his lowest total in any season in which he has appeared in at least 65 games. Klingberg's power-play production was also way down, as his 10 points with the man advantage were also a near career low. He had to settle for a one-year contract once again, this year with Toronto at a shade over $4 million. Klingberg is an ideal bounce-back candidate assuming he can earn a spot on Toronto's top power-play unit, which is no guarantee considering Morgan Rielly is still in the picture.

Sandin struggled to find his footing in 52 games with the Maple Leafs (four goals, 20 points) last season, but he exploded following a late-February trade to Washington, posting 15 points in 19 games with his new club. It's worth noting a good chunk of that production came when John Carlson was out with an injury and Sandin was running the club's top power-play unit. The defensive depth for Washington is questionable at best, meaning the 23-year-old Sandin should be primed for a major role in 2023-24, even with Carlson back to full health. Don't forget about Sandin in the later rounds on draft day.

Things seemed to sour between Dach and the Blackhawks toward the end of his run in Chicago but trading a 21-year-old No. 3 overall pick is typically bad business. Dach missed a good chunk of his first year in Montreal in 2022-23 due to injury, but he had by far his best season to date (14 goals, 38 points, 16 power-play points in 58 games) when healthy. Dach should be a full go for training camp and one of the key offensive pieces for a rebuilding Montreal team, giving him sneaky mid-round fantasy upside in most formats.

What ended up being Hall's final season in Boston was derailed by a lower-body injury which cost him about a month and a half's worth of action from late February to mid-April last year. He ended up playing in 61 games, posting 16 goals and 36 points, his lowest point total in any campaign in which he appeared in at least 54 games. With two years remaining on his contract at an annual cap hit of $6 million, Hall was traded to Chicago in late June in what amounted to a salary dump. The former Hart Trophy winner will see a much larger role with the Blackhawks and will serve as a solid veteran mentor for 2023 No. 1 overall pick Connor Bedard, although it's difficult to see him posting more than 60 points along with an ugly plus-minus rating this year.

Sprong had a career year in 2022-23 in what would end up being his lone season in Seattle. He racked up 21 goals and 46 points in 66 games. He also performed well with the man advantage, finishing with six power-play goals and 14 points a man up. Just 26-years-old, you would think Sprong would be a player teams would love to have, but the Kraken declined to make him a qualifying offer, allowing Sprong to sign a one-year, $2 million deal with Detroit. He could easily match his numbers from last year if he earns a spot in the top six for the Red Wings in 2023-24, but that's far from a guarantee given the team's forward depth.

While he didn't post the same type of numbers as some of his superstar teammates, Chytil's improvements were among the most positive developments for the Rangers in 2022-23. He appeared in 74 games and set new career-best marks in goals (22), assists (23), points (45) and shots on goal (177). He had a particularly good stretch in the middle of the year, scoring seven times in a five-game span. Chytil, who will turn 24  right before training camp begins, is a definite injury risk given his history, but should he remain healthy, the four-year, $17.75 extension the Rangers handed him this past March will look like a bargain.

The No. 5 overall pick in the 2018 draft, it took Hayton three NHL seasons to find his footing, but he got there last year. He played in all 82 games for Arizona, tallying 19 goals, 43 points, 178 shots on goal and 10 points with the man advantage. Hayton's minus-five rating was also perfectly reasonable given the fact he played for one of the worst teams in the league. With the Coyotes still neck deep in their seemingly never-ending rebuild, Hayton will again be tasked with taking on a massive role for Arizona in 2023-24, making him a late-round pick in fantasy drafts.

The No. 2 overall pick in the 2021 Draft out of the University of Michigan, Beniers led all rookies in both goals (24) and points (57) in first full NHL campaign in 2022-23, eventually winning the Calder Trophy as NHL Rookie of the Year. He also added seven points in 14 postseason contests. It's impossible to argue with that production from a 20-year-old, but Beniers finished with just 148 shots on goal and 10 power-play points in 80 games, so his secondary numbers don't jump off the page. It's reasonable to expect some improvement from Beniers in 2023-24, but those expecting a league-winning type of season seem likely to come away disappointed. Keep expectations in check.

We're just three years out, but it seems clear at this point that Stutzle, who went No. 3 overall, is going to be the best player to come out of the 2020 draft. The talented German is coming off a season in which he set new career-best marks in goals (39), assists (51), points (90), shots on goal (228), power-play points (28) and average ice time (21:16). The lone concern was Stutzle's 17.1 shooting percentage, a number considerably higher than we've seen from him in the past. Even with some minor regression in that area, Stutzle projects as an elite fantasy play in 2023-24.

Armed with a full no-move clause in his contract, Kane, a future first-ballot Hall of Famer, negotiated a trade to the Rangers in late February following parts of sixteen seasons with the Blackhawks. Bothered by a nagging hip issue and a poor fit on a team that already had more than enough crafty playmakers, Kane managed six goals and 18 points in 26 combined regular season and playoff games with New York. As was widely expected, Kane underwent hip surgery in late May which is expected to require four to six months of recovery. There's a very real chance we won't see Kane, a current unrestricted free agent, until after Christmas, at which point he'll presumably choose a contending team to sign with for the stretch run.

Kuznetsov's 2022-23 campaign was underwhelming on multiple fronts. He played in 81 of 82 regular-season games for Washington but managed just 12 goals and 55 points. Kuznetsov finished with a horrifying minus-26 rating, and his power-play production dipped considerably from 27 points two seasons ago to just 18 last year. The struggles directly coincided with a reduced role. Kuznetsov logged 18:04 of ice time per game on average last season, down from 20:17 the year prior, and his time with the man advantage dipped from 3:44 per game to 2:49 per contest last season. The lone bit of good news is that Kuznetsov is due for some positive regression after converting on just seven percent of his shots last season, well below his average mark. Still, it's hard to get excited about him as anything more than a low-floor, mid-to-late round fantasy option.

The Capitals inked Strome to a one-year, $3.5 million deal in free agency last summer and were rewarded with a career-high 23 goals and 65 points (21 with the man advantage) in 81 games. The days of Strome playing on a bargain-rate contract have come and gone, as Washington extended him for five years and $25 million this past February. It feels as if Strome has been around forever, but he won't turn 27 until next March. With Nicklas Backstrom nearing the end of his career and Evgeni Kuznetsov struggling to find his game, Strome has a real chance to serve as Washington's No. 1 center in 2023-24.

Fantasy managers got another full season from Stamkos in 2022-23, as he appeared in 81 of 82 games for a second straight year. His offensive numbers were way down (34 goals, 84 points) when compared to 2021-22 (42 goals, 106 points), but at north of a point-per-game, Stamkos was well worth the early-round pick he cost last year. Stamkos will be 34 next February, but there's a case to be made that he's due for positive regression on the heels of a season in which he posted a 14.2 shooting percentage, by far his lowest mark since 2017-18. The days of Stamkos posting 100-plus points have likely come and gone, but his numbers from last year seem like a fair barometer for what to expect in 2023-24.

Petry's first and only season in 2022-23 in Pittsburgh was a bit of a mixed bag. He missed 21 games due to injury. He did post 30-plus points (31) for the fifth time in six seasons, and his 201 combined hits/blocks were his most since the 2018-19 campaign. Needing to move out salary to acquire Erik Karlsson from San Jose, the Penguins returned Petry to Montreal in a three-team deal. It seemed like a solid landing spot from a fantasy perspective, but the Canadiens subsequently flipped Petry to his home state Red Wings in mid-August. He's a little less intriguing as a mid-round fantasy pick in Motown given Detroit's defensive depth.

The Jets improved considerably as a team a season ago, but Dubois' individual numbers were right in line with his first year with the club. He posted 27 goals and 63 points in 73 games in 2022-23, including 23 points with the man advantage. Set to become an unrestricted free agent in the summer of 2024 and having informed Winnipeg he wouldn't be signing an extension with the team, the Jets shipped Dubois to the Kings in late June. He was rewarded with a new eight-year, $68 million deal in the process. Dubois is being paid like a low-end No. 1 center, but Anze Kopitar, who also recently signed an extension, is currently locked into that role for LA. As a result, Dubois may struggle to see a significant increase in production in 2023-24.

Dorofeyev's opportunities at the NHL level a season go were few and far between, but he certainly played well when given the chance. He tallied seven goals and nine points in 18 games with Vegas, chipping in three points with the man advantage for good measure. While the production was great, it's worth noting Dorofeyev's 17.5 shooting percentage is unsustainable. The 22-year-old would appear to have a pretty good chance of cracking the Opening Night lineup for the Golden Knights in 2023-24, but even if he does, Dorofeyev is unlikely to receive the sort of usage that leads to desirable fantasy production.

Nelson doesn't get talked about much as a top-flight goal scorer, but he's lit the lamp 73 times in 154 games over the past two seasons. His assist total was way up in 2022-23, as he finished with 39 after never posting more than 28 in any prior year. The result was a career-high 75 points, including 17 with the man advantage. Nelson also shot the puck more than ever in 2022-23, finishing with 222 shots on goal. On the surface, it's an intriguing package from a fantasy perspective, just keep in mind Nelson will be 32 years of age shortly after the season begins, and he plays for a team that has struggled to generate offense over the last couple years.

Kane missed exactly half of Edmonton's 82 regular-season games a season ago, first missing two months following a scary incident in which his wrist was cut by a skate blade before sitting out another three weeks later in the year with an upper-body issue. Kane was reasonably effective when healthy, managing 16 goals and 28 points along with 124 hits. The main concern regarding Kane's 2023-24 fantasy outlook is his limited power-play production. He doesn't play on Edmonton's No. 1 unit and saw just 90 seconds of ice time per game with the man advantage last season, managing a measly two assists while a man up. Unless Kane's role in that department noticeably improves in 2023-24, his upside will be limited.

Compher picked a great time to have a career year. With the Avalanche battling the injury bug all season long, Compher saw his role increase in a major way in 2022-23. He appeared in all 82 games, scoring 17 goals and a career-high 52 points. The bump in production was largely the result of his expanded role with the man advantage. Compher had 14 power-play points after managing just 13 in his previous 185 games combined. The Red Wings were impressed enough to extend Compher a five-year, $25.5 million deal in free agency. The financial commitment suggests Detroit has big plans for Compher in 2023-24, but a slight decrease in scoring should be expected as he'll be playing for a weaker team.

2022-23 was a lost season for Brown, who appeared in just four games for the Captials before tearing his ACL and undergoing surgery which ended his year. He elected to sign a one-year, $4 million deal with Edmonton in free agency. It goes without saying it's a potentially awesome landing spot from a fantasy standpoint. While it's not a guarantee, any player who might line up alongside either Connor McDavid or Leon Draisaitl is immediately worth monitoring. Keep on eye on Brown in training camp, as he's a player with the potential to really move the needle in your league this year.

Playing in his age-31 season, Fowler appeared in all 82 games for the rebuilding Ducks last year, reaching double-digit goals (10) for the third time while finishing with a career-best 48 points. Fowler was also a minus-23, his worst rating since the 2011-12 season when he was a 19-year-old. Anaheim added a couple forwards to the mix this offseason, but they made no notable additions on defense, at least none that will threaten Fowler's role with the man advantage. He offers little in terms of hits and his plus-minus rating will be likely once again be woeful, but Fowler seems like a pretty good bet to top the 40-point mark for a third straight season in 2023-24.

Seeking to cash in as an unrestricted free agent for the first time in his career, Killorn got paid in a major way, signing a four-year, $25 million deal with the Ducks on July 1. The contract comes on the heels of a season in which Killorn played in all 82 games for Tampa Bay for a second straight year, posting career-best marks in goals (27), assists (37) and points (64) while finishing with a dozen power-play points for the third time in four years. From a fantasy perspective, managers need to look no further than Ryan Strome for a cautionary tale in terms of how this could turn out. Strome joined Anaheim last season after three productive years with the Rangers, managing just 41 points along with a horrific minus-30 rating. There's far more risk than reward here with Killorn, especially considering he's expected to be sidelined until at least November with a fractured finger suffered during training camp.

You likely had to spend a first-round pick to acquire Makar in fantasy drafts a year ago, and although he was more than worth the investment when he played, Makar ended up missing 22 of Colorado's 82 regular-season games in 2022-23. He finished the year with 17 goals and 66 points (including 30 with the man advantage), numbers that average out to a similar pace from what we saw from him in his breakout 2021-22 campaign. Makar is largely considered the most dynamic and talented defender in the game today. If you're comfortable with his minor injury concerns, Makar may be available at a semi-discount in fantasy drafts this year. He could easily finish the year as the No. 1 fantasy rearguard if he can make it through the season in one piece.

MacKinnon has as much natural ability as any player in the NHL not named Connor McDavid. He's coming off a season in which he set new career-best marks in goals (42), assists (69), points (111), shots on goal (366) and average ice time (22:19). MacKinnon finished fifth in the NHL in scoring and trailed only Boston's David Pastrnak in shots on goal. All this despite missing nearly all of December with an upper-body issue. Set to turn 28 in early September, MacKinnon is primed for another monster campaign in 2023-24, making him an easy top-10 selection in all formats.

Rantanen cost a pretty penny in fantasy drafts last year. He ended up being a value pick, setting new career-best marks in goals (55), points (105), shots on goal (306), power-play points (37), average ice time (22:13) and hits (77). Rantanen's shooting percentage of 18 was high but not astronomically so considering what we've seen from him in the past. He may not hit the 55-goal plateau again, but 45-plus markers should be well within reach for him in 2023-24. Betting on an uber-talented 26-year-old that plays for one of the NHL's best teams is good business, so don't be afraid to spend a first-round pick on Rantanen in your draft this year.

There was always very little chance Josi was going to be able to match his ridiculous 23-goal, 96-point effort from 2021-22 in 2022-23, and he didn't, finishing with 18 goals and 59 points in 67 games. With Nashville out of the playoff hunt, Josi sat out the Predators' final 15 games of the season with an upper-body ailment. The good news is Josi remained an elite fantasy option by almost any measure last season. He had 269 shots on goal, 24 power-play points and 197 combined hits/blocks while averaging north of 25 minutes per game (25:10) for the fourth time in the past five years. Now 33 years of age, Josi once again looks like a dependable No. 1 fantasy defender heading into the 2023-24 campaign.

Remember the days of getting Robertson at a discount in your fantasy draft? They're over. As they should be considering he's coming off a season in which he finished tied for sixth in NHL scoring with 109 points in 82 games. Robertson's 46 goals placed him seventh in the league, and his 41 points with the man advantage were third in the NHL, trailing only a trio of Oilers (Connor McDavid, Leon Draisaitl, Ryan Nugent-Hopkins) and Nikita Kucherov. His breakout season looks entirely sustainable considering Robertson's shooting percentage dropped significantly last year (14.7 percent) compared to 2021-22 (18.6). Invest with confidence.

On the surface, it appears as if Kaprizov had a bit of a disappointing 2022-23 season. His 40 goals and 75 points were a far cry from the 47 goals and 108 points he posted two years ago, but it's worth noting he missed nearly a month late in the year with a lower-body injury. There were plenty of other positives. Kaprizov's 32 points with the man advantage were a new high-water mark, and he also managed to pot 40 goals for a second consecutive season despite the fact his shooting percentage dropped from 16.3 percent to 15.3 percent. One of the most naturally gifted players in the NHL, Kaprizov, who is still just 26 years old, should again threaten the century mark in scoring if he can make it through the 2023-24 campaign in one piece.

Konecny was just about the lone bright spot for a dreadful Flyers team in 2022-23. He scored a career-high 31 goals and averaged better than a point-per-game (61 points in 60 games) for the first time. The bad news is he missed 22 games with a pair of upper-body ailments. Konecny's 16.2 shooting percentage was high, making him a prime regression candidate in the goals-scored department in 2023-24, but he's also a lock for a ton of playing time, particularly with the man advantage, on what may be the league's least-talented team. Keep Konecny's injury history in mind on draft day, but there should be enough offensive production here to make Konecny a rock-solid fantasy option this year.

A defensive-minded center with little offensive production during the first five years of his NHL career, Eriksson Ek has taken a giant leap forward over the last two seasons, highlighted by a career-best 61 points (23 goals) in 78 games last season. He spent the entire year on Minnesota's top power-play unit, adding a whopping 23 points with the man advantage. Eriksson Ek played in every game for the Wild until suffering a lower-body injury late in the season. He missed the club's final four regular-season games in addition to five of six playoff contests. In the one postseason game he did play, Eriksson Ek lasted just one shift, or 19 seconds. The injury, later revealed to be a broken fibula, is expected to be fully healed by training camp, potentially making Eriksson Ek an underrated fantasy option heading into 2023-24.

Hintz missed a couple weeks in the middle of the 2022-23 campaign with a lower-body ailment, but he was once again dynamite when in the lineup, posting numbers (37 goals, 75 points, 184 shots on goal, 21 power-play points) similar to what we saw from him two seasons ago. His plus-31 rating was also a new career-best mark by a wide margin. The lone concerning statistic was Hintz's astronomical 20.1 shooting percentage, but three minutes' worth of power-play time per game should help offset that gaudy number likely reverting to the mean in 2023-24. Hintz projects as a rock-solid No. 2 fantasy center on draft day.

Forsberg played in all of Nashville's first 50 games of the 2022-23 campaign before an upper-body injury ended his season. There were reports in late February that his return was "imminent," but we never saw him again, which suggests there may have been a setback along the way. Forsberg was his usual productive self prior to the injury (19 goals, 42 points), although he was well off the pace of his massive 2021-22 campaign (42 goals, 82 points in 69 games). There's nothing to suggest the injury is a long-term issue, but the status of Forsberg bears watching as training camp gets under way. The injury concern combined with Nashville's lack of offensive firepower makes Forsberg a high-risk, high-reward fantasy play for 2023-24.

With John Klingberg off to Anaheim, Heiskanen finally got a chance to serve as Dallas' No. 1 power-play quarterback in 2022-23, and he responded in a major way. The talented Finn sets new career-best marks across the board (11 goals, 62 assists, 73 points, plus-12 rating, 206 shots on goal, 25:29 average time on ice per game), while Heiskanen's 34 points with the man advantage tied him with Vancouver's Quinn Hughes for the NHL lead among defenders. There's a real case to be made that Heiskanen has the highest upside from a fantasy perspective of any rearguard not named Cale Makar. Set to play this entire season at age 24, Heiskanen is worth the pretty penny he will cost on draft day this year.

Pavelski hasn't missed a single regular-season game for the Stars over the past two seasons. His numbers a year ago -- 28 goals, 77 points (27 with the man advantage), 184 shots on goal and 93 hits -- were nearly identical to what we saw during the previous season. Pavelski's plus-42 rating was also by far the best mark of his 17-year NHL career. The Wisconsin native did suffer a concussion in the playoffs which cost him five games, but Pavelski returned to action for each of Dallas' final 13 postseason contests, scoring nine goals while averaging a point-per-game. Pavelski's fantasy floor is stable because of his power-play production, but betting on a player that will play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 39 is risky business.

Fresh off signing a massive eight-year, $49 million deal with the Avalanche in July of 2022, Nichushkin was excellent when in the lineup in 2022-23, which didn't happen very often. He missed 29 of Colorado's 82 regular-season games, posting 17 goals, 47 points (16 on the power play), 158 shots on goal and a plus-15 rating. A baffling scene occurred while in Seattle during Colorado's first-round playoff series. Nichushkin was sent home suddenly and didn't appear in any of the team's final five playoff games, and the Avalanche didn't shed much light on the situation. It was later revealed there was an incident at the team hotel which caused the police to get involved, but the NHL investigated and cleared Nichushkin of any wrongdoing, confirming he's eligible to play in 2023-24. Back to full health, that makes the big man a potential buy-low pick in fantasy leagues this year.

Toews was an excellent fantasy asset once again last year, notching 50-plus points (50) for a second straight season while adding new career-best marks in shots on goal (165), hits (93) and blocks (138). Over the course of 146 regular-season games over the past two seasons combined, Toews has a ridiculous plus-91 rating. His average power-play time per game increased to 2:02 last year, but that was the result of Cale Makar being in and out of the lineup for much of the campaign. Once you get past the big boys, it's difficult to find an all-around defensive fantasy weapon as useful as Toews.

The poster boy for Columbus' train wreck of a 2022-23 season, Werenski played just 13 games (three goals, eight points) before suffering a shoulder injury which required surgery and ended his year. He began skating with the team in early March, so he should be fully healed by training camp. Nonetheless, Werenski's fantasy value remains a bit uncertain heading into 2023-24. On top of coming off the injury, the Blue Jackets added multiple defenders this offseason (Ivan Provorov, Damon Severson) with a history of seeing power-play time. Werenski is by far the most talented of the bunch, but even a minor dip in usage with the man advantage could be enough to hamper his fantasy value. Keep an eye on the situation under new head coach Mike Babcock.

Zuccarello's production declined in 2022-23 (22 goals, 67 points in 78 games) when compared to his shocking 2021-22 campaign (24 goals, 79 points in 70 games), but he was still plenty effective. Zucc's 198 shots on goal, 29 power-play points and 20:12 average ice time in 2022-23 represented new career-best marks, which is remarkable for a guy that played the entire season at age 35. Zuccarello is a risky fantasy bet this year simply duet to his advanced age, but there's upside here given his massive role with the man advantage and the presence of a top-flight running mate in Kirill Kaprizov.

Taking advantage of increased playing time on a rebuilding Flyers team, Tippett had a career-best season last year. He set new high-water marks in games played (77), goals (27), assists (22), points (49), shots on goal (231), power-play points (12) and hits (125). Tippett concluded the season especially strong, with nine goals and 15 points in his final 15 games. Philadelphia is likely going to be one of the worst teams in the NHL in 2023-24, meaning Tippett is looking at another poor plus-minus rating (he was minus-17 last year), but it's not out of the realm of possibility that he'll crack the 30-goal plateau for the first time this year given his guaranteed role with the Flyers.

O'Reilly was traded from St. Louis to the Maple Leafs in late February and played eight games with his new club before blocking a shot that resulted in a broken thumb. He ended up missing a month before returning for a handful of regular-season games and Toronto's entire postseason run. Overall, O'Reilly managed just 30 points in 53 games between his two stops, his lowest total since he was a 21-year-old with the Avalanche in 2012-13. O'Reilly signed a four-year, $18 million deal with Nashville as a free agent this summer and is in line to open the season as the club's No. 1 center following the trade of Ryan Johansen and the buyout of Matt Duchene, but it would still be surprising to see the veteran crack the 60-point mark in 2023-24.

Provorov has been trending in the wrong direction for a while and last season felt like rock bottom. In 82 games he managed just six goals and 27 points. He finished with a minus-17 rating and tallied only 115 shots on goal. Coming from a player that posted 203 shots in 2017-18, that's noteworthy. In a full-blown rebuild, the Flyers traded Provorov to Columbus in early June. The Russian defender has always been durable, so there's hope that he may find his footing in more of a defensive role with the Blue Jackets. There's bounce-back potential here, giving Provorov mid-to-late round fantasy appeal in this year's drafts.

Boldy logged his first full NHL season in 2022-23, posting numbers (31 goals, 63 points, 26 power-play points in 81 games) right in line with what we saw from him in his abbreviated 47-game debut in 2021-22. The one main difference was Boldy's increase in playing time. His overall average ice time jumped from 15:22 to 18:30, while his average ice time with the man advantage jumped from 2:21 to 3:48. Set to play nearly the entirety of this upcoming season at age 22, Boldy's significant power-play usage should help offset any potential slumps he may endure through the year, making him a rock-solid, mid-round fantasy asset.

Plenty of Flyers disappointed in 2022-23, and Sanheim was near the top of the list. He managed a woeful seven goals and 23 points in 81 games, averaging 20:24 worth of ice time per game, way below the 22:58 he averaged a year prior. To make matters worse, Philadelphia signed Sanheim to a new eight-year, $50 million extension last October. The deal begins in 2023-24 and runs through the 2030-31 campaign. Sanheim is still just 27-years-old, so there's time for him to turn it around, but if he doesn't, his contract could be one of the worst in the NHL sooner rather than later.

Couturier missed the entire 2022-23 season with a back injury. In fact, he last played a game on December 18 of 2021. "Coots" was skating on his own around last year's All-Star break in hopes of returning late in the year, but the Flyers, during a lost season, officially shut him down in early April. There have been no concrete updates since, so Couturier should be considered a bad bet to remain healthy in 2023-24. even if he's ultimately ready for the start of the campaign.

"Johnny Hockey" arrived in Columbus last season following eight years in Calgary, and the move was a bit of a letdown for all parties involved. The Blue Jackets were again one of the NHL's worst teams, and Gaudreau finished with 21 goals and 74 points, a far cry from the 40 goals and 115 points he posted in 2021-22. Most concerning of all was Gaudreau's plus-minus rating. He led the league in that category two years ago at plus-64 before dropping to a woeful minus-33 in his first year with the Jackets. Common sense dictates things can only get better for Gaudreau, a player with a long track record of fantasy success, so he's worth a look in the middle rounds of fantasy pools this year, especially given his likely dip in average draft position.

Benn's days as a reliable fantasy asset appeared to be over on the heels of a 2021-22 campaign which saw him post just 18 goals and 46 points in 82 games. As a result, it would have been impossible to predict the stellar season he put together a year ago. Buoyed by a career-high 17.4 shooting percentage, Benn posted 33 goals in 2022-23, his most since 2017-18. His plus-23 rating was a new career high, and he added exactly 30 points with the man advantage for the second time in fourteen NHL seasons. Benn has always been durable and he's typically good for at least 100 hits per season, giving him value in formats which value them, but expecting the same type of offensive production he had a year ago in his age-34 season in 2023-24 is probably too much to ask.

Jenner missed a month in the middle of the season with a broken thumb and Columbus' final three games with a back issue, but he was one of the club's few bright spots when healthy. He closed with 26 goals, 45 points (11 with the man advantage) and 214 shots on goal, his highest totals since 2015-16. That's the good news. The bad news is there isn't a heck of a lot of fantasy upside here, but 25 goals, 50 points and 150 hits would seem to be well within reach for Jenner in 2023-24, making him a serviceable depth option in fantasy circles.

Byram played a little more than half the season for Colorado last year due to injury and illness, but his promise was on full display when he was in the lineup. He posted 10 goals and 24 points in 42 games, averaging nearly 22 minutes of ice time per game (21:53) while chipping in a six power-play points for good measure. Set to play this entire season at age 22, Bowen's long-term potential is immense, but the presence of Cale Makar and to a lesser extent Devon Toews makes him a better keeper/dynasty league asset than a re-draft option.

Marchenko made his NHL debut last season and came out firing. He appeared in 59 games for the Blue Jackets, tallying 21 goals while adding four assists. Marchenko may struggle to duplicate that type of success in 2023-24, but he's going to have mid-round fantasy value due to his upside. That said, Marchenko's floor is scary because he has little to fall back upon if the goals dry up. Keep that in mind on draft day.

Lehkonen cruised to career-best marks in his first full season with the Avalanche in 2022-23, posting 21 goals and 51 points in just 64 games. He missed a month late in the year with a broken finger. Lehkonen's increased production was directly tied to a significant bump in usage with the man advantage. Averaging 3:32 of power-play time per game, Lehkonen tallied 20 points with the man advantage, which came on the heels of a measly 11 power-play points in his first six NHL seasons combined. Colorado added Ryan Johansen, Ross Colton and Jonathan Drouin this offseason, but the club also announced captain Gabriel Landeskog will miss a second straight season due to a serious knee injury, meaning Lehkonen's top-line role on one of the NHL's best teams should remain secure.

The emergence of Novak, a 26-year-old journeyman, in 2022-23 was perhaps the only thing that went right for Nashville. A University of Minnesota product who has spent most of his professional career in the AHL and ECHL, Novak played 51 games for the Predators last year, managing 17 goals and 43 points including 12 with the man advantage. It's a feel-good story and one that deserves more credit than it's gotten, but it might be unsustainable. For starters, Filip Forsberg will be returning from injury and Ryan O'Reilly signed with Nashville as a free agent. Novak's presumably unsustainable 18.3 shooting percentage from a year ago should also come into consideration. Novak showed enough last season to make you believe he's a long-term NHL regular, and there's still a chance he'll become one in 2023-24, but fantasy managers should approach with caution on draft day.

Like virtually all of his teammates, Laine's 2022-23 season was underwhelming. Injuries limited him to just 55 games, although he did manage 22 goals and 52 points when healthy. He scored on Opening Night against Carolina but was injured in the process and ending up missing the next six games. He missed two weeks in November with an ankle issue before sitting out Columbus' final 12 games with a triceps injury. Laine is a theoretical bounce-back candidate, especially in terms of his production with the man advantage alongside playmaker Johnny Gaudreau, but Laine has played just 111 games over the last two seasons combined, making him a significant injury risk. Take that into account on draft day.

Spurgeon is by no means a league-winner, but he's been a solid mid-round fantasy option for years now and the 2022-23 campaign was no exception. The Wild captain appeared in 79 games, posting 11 goals, 34 points and a plus-32 rating. His power-play production really dropped off last season, from 14 points with the man advantage two seasons ago to just four last year, but it was otherwise another solid campaign for Spurgeon. He should be considered more of a safe floor than a high-ceiling player from a fantasy perspective, but acquiring dependable depth is never a bad move on draft day.

Barrie was very good in the early portion of last season, posting 10 goals and 43 points in 61 games while quarterbacking Edmonton's league-best No. 1 power-play unit. Despite his strong performance, Barrie was dealt to Nashville in late February in the trade involving Mattias Ekholm. Barrie's point production dipped (3 goals, 12 points in 24 games) with his new team, although he was still reasonably effective. It's worth noting Nashville captain Roman Josi was out of the lineup for the vast majority of Barrie's late-season run with the club, so it remains unclear how new Predators coach Andrew Brunette will deploy the two in 2023-24. It would, however, be shocking to see Josi removed from the No. 1 unit, meaning Barrie could be looking at a decreased role with the man advantage, which would negatively impact his fantasy value in a significant way.

Tomasino split last season between Nashville (5 goals, 18 points in 31 games) and AHL Milwaukee (12 goals, 32 points in 38 games) and was productive at both stops. The former 2019 first-rounder was a big scorer in his junior days and appears primed to grab a full-time gig, possibly in the top six, for the Predators in 2023-24. Nashville's biggest weakness is a lack of difference makers up front, so the club should be more than willing to hand Tomasino a significant role in 2023-24 and let the chips fall where they may.

Lindell has settled into a useful middle-pairing role for the Stars, contributing in all areas while not really excelling in any. He's scored somewhere between 23-25 points in three of the past four seasons while chipping in roughly 100 hits and 150 blocks per campaign for good measure. Lindell's plus-29 rating in 2022-23 was a new career-high, but that stat tends to fluctuate on a year-to-year basis. He's a solid player that helps Dallas win hockey games on a nightly basis, but he shouldn't be expected to emerge as a high-end fantasy option in 2023-24.

The No. 3 overall pick in the 2023 draft, Fantilli won the Hobey Baker Award as the best player in college hockey in his lone season at the University of Michigan after tallying a ridiculous 30 goals and 65 points in 36 games for the Wolverines last year. He might not be Connor Bedard, but Fantilli is unquestionably one of the best prospects to enter the NHL in quite some time. Already signed to his entry-level deal, Fantilli is set to play this upcoming season for the Blue Jackets. Despite his immense potential, Fantilli should be considered a late-round re-draft pick, but he'll be one of the best keeper/dynasty assets available in this year's drafts.

Seguin has remained relatively healthy over the past two seasons, missing just seven regular-season games over that span, but his production was nowhere near what we saw in his heyday. Seguin finished with 50 points in 2022-23, which came on the heels of his 49-point performance in 2021-22. A player that tallied 300-plus shots in three straight years not long ago, Seguin managed just 189 shots on goal last season. Now 31 years of age, don't overpay for Seguin on draft day. 25 goals and 60 points would seem to be Seguin's absolute ceiling at this point, making him a fringe asset in standard formats.

If you draft Peeke for your fantasy roster, you know what you're getting. He has just eight goals and 28 points over 162 games over the past two years, but Peeke has also generated 371 hits and 366 blocks in that span, making him a legitimate option in leagues which value such stats. Keep in mind, however, that Peeke was a minus-41 in 2022-23. He won't be asked to log so many minutes with Damon Severson and Ivan Provorov joining the Blue Jackets, but Columbus still projects to be a poor team in 2023-24. The risk may not out way the potential reward.

Girard is coming off one of the quietest 37-point seasons you will ever see. He added new high-water marks in shots on goal (119) and blocked shots (116) while averaging north of 21 minutes (21:30) of ice time for a fourth straight year. Girard would probably do exceptionally well if he was ever granted an extended run on Colorado's top power-play unit, but with Cale Makar, Devon Toews, and Bowen Byram around, that simply won't be happening in 2023-24. As is, fantasy managers will have to settle for solid, if unspectacular production from the 2016 second-rounder.

Evangelista became a regular for the injury-riddled Predators starting in late February and showed well in the process. He appeared in 24 games, posting seven goals and 15 points. Evangelista had a pair of multi-goal games in addition to a pair of three-point contests. The 2020 second-rounder (42nd overall) had 55 goals and 111 points in 62 games in his final OHL season, so he can clearly score. Keep an eye on where Evangelista lines up in training camp, as his usage will determine his fantasy outlook for 2023-24.

Laughton is best served playing in a middle-six role on a contending team, but with the Flyers lacking offensive weapons, he saw his usage increase significantly in 2022-23. The end result was a career-high 18 goals and 43 points in 78 games. Laughton added nine points with the man advantage after managing just two power-play points in his first eight NHL seasons combined. That's certainly not league-winning production, but when combined with upwards of 150 hits per season, Laughton is in the discussion for a late-round pick in deeper fantasy formats.

With Dougie Hamilton back to full health, Severson's offensive numbers were way down in 2022-23. He managed just 33 points in 81 games, this on the heels of an 80-game, 46-point performance the year prior. Clearly not deterred by the dip in output, Columbus agreed to a sign-and-trade with the Devils to acquire Severson in June, handing him an eight-year, $50 million deal in the process. It's a big chunk of change to pay, but Severson is still just 29 and has been very durable throughout the course of his career. His production from this past season is a fair representation of what to expect moving forward.

Hakanpaa has been a regular on the Dallas blue line over the past three seasons, playing a tough, rugged style while adding little-to-no offense. His six goals and 16 points last year were a new career high. Where Hakanpaa makes his living from a fantasy standpoint is in the hits/blocks department. He contributed 352 combined hits/blocks in 2022-23 on the heels of a 2021-22 campaign during which he posted 360. If your league places an emphasis on those stats, feel free to take the plunge on draft day. Hakanpaa underwent offseason knee surgery after battling the injury in the postseason, but he should be ready to go by the time training camp rolls around.

Boqvist was plenty effective (five goals, 24 points in 46 games) in 2022-23, but he was rarely in the lineup. He missed nearly two months early in the year with a broken foot before sitting out a handful of games with other injuries the rest of the way. Boqvist offers little in terms of hits and blocks and he's posted a negative plus-minus rating in each of his four NHL seasons, so it's imperative that he pile up the points to provide any fantasy value. With Zach Werenski returning to full health and Damon Severson and Ivan Provorov acquired via trade, the risk doesn't seem to be worth the reward here.
